ision_type1               = State\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_type4               = [[Taluk]]\n| subdivision_name1               =[[Karnataka]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Dakshina Kannada]]\n| subdivision_name4               = [[Mangalore taluk|Mangalore]]\n| established_title               = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date                = \n| founder                         = \n| named_for                       = [[Mangaladevi]]\n| government_type                 = [[Mayor\u2013council government|Mayor\u2013Council]]\n| governing_body                  = [[Mangalore City Corporation]]\n| leader_title                    = Mayor\n| leader_name                     = Diwakara ([[Bharatiya Janata Party|BJP]])<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/diwakara-from-bjp-elected-mayor-of-mangaluru/article30942290.ece|title=Diwakara from BJP elected Mayor of Mangaluru|date=28 February 2020|newspaper=The Hindu|accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n| leader_title1                   = Deputy Mayor\n| leader_name1                    = \n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  =<ref name=\"area-info\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mangalorecity.mrc.gov.in/|title=Mangalore City Corporation|publisher=[[Mangalore City Corporation]]|access-date=20 February 2017}}</ref>\n| area_total_km2                  = 184\n| area_rank                       = \n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = 22\n| population_total                = 484785<ref name=\"table 2\">{{cite web |title=Cities having population 1 lakh and above |url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_2_PR_Cities_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf |publisher=Census of india |accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref>\n| population_as_of                = 2011\n| population_footnotes            = \n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| population_metro                = 619664<ref name=\"table 3\">{{cite web |title=Urban Agglomerations/Cities having population 1 lakh and above |url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_3_PR_UA_Citiees_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf |publisher=Census of India |accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref>\n| population_demonym              = ''[[Mangalorean]]'', ''Ma\u1e45ga\u1e37\u016brinavaru'', ''Kudladhar'', ''Maikalathanga'', ''Mangaluriga'', ''Kodialcho'', ''Ko\u1e0diy\u0101\u1e37gar''\n| demographics_type1              = Languages\n| demographics1_title1            = Administrative\n| demographics1_info1             = <!-- Don't add Tulu. It is not Administrative language yet--> [[Kannada Language|Kannada]], [[English language|English]] <!-- HIDDEN EDITOR NOTE: DO NOT CHANGE THESE ENTRIES ANYMORE. EDITS WILL BE REVERTED-->\n| demographics1_title2            = Regional\n| demographics1_info2             = <!-- HIDDEN EDITOR NOTE: DO NOT ADD ANY MORE ENTRIES. EDITS WILL BE REVERTED--> [[Tulu language|Tulu]], [[Konkani language|Konkani]], [[Beary language|Beary]], [[Koraga language|Koraga]], [[Havyaka Kannada]]<!-- HIDDEN EDITOR NOTE: MALAYALAM IS NOT REGIONAL IN MANGALURU-->\n<!-- HIDDEN EDITOR NOTE: INCLUSION OF REGIONS SUCH AS TULU NADU/COASTAL KARNATAKA/MYSORE DIVISION NEED CONSENSUS. KINDLY DON'T ADD YOUR POINT OF VIEW-->\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code                     = 575001 to 575030<ref name=\"pcode\">{{cite web|url=http://pincode.net.in/KARNATAKA/DAKSHINA_KANNADA/M/MANGALORE|title=Pin Code: Mangalore, Dakshina Kannada, Karnataka|access-date=8 February 2020|publisher=PINcode.Net.In}}</ref>\n| area_code                       = [[Telephone numbers in India|+91-(0824)]]\n| area_code_type                  = Telephone code\n| registration_plate              = KA-19, KA-62<ref>{{cite news |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mangaluru/surathkal-all-set-to-get-a-new-rto-in-next-20-days/articleshow/57189024.cms|title=Surathkal all set to get a new RTO in next 20 days|date=16 February 2017|accessdate=13 March 2020|newspaper=The Times of India|author=Jaideep Shenoy}}</ref>\n| blank_name_sec1                 = [[human sex ratio|Sex ratio]]\n| blank_info_sec1                 = 0.984<!--1000 M/1016 F--><!--cited in edit summary to \"census 2011 mangalore data\"--><ref>{{cite web |url=http://censuskarnataka.gov.in/presentation-PCA-2011-Press%20Release.pdf|title=Primary census abstract data highlights|accessdate=5 March 2020|publisher=censuskarnataka.gov.in|p=69|author=T K Anil Kumar}}</ref>\n| blank1_name_sec1                = [[Human Development Index]]\n| blank1_info_sec1                = {{increase}} 0.83 ({{as of|alt=as of 2015|2015}})<ref name=\"hdi\">{{cite news\n|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Mangalore/human-development-index-dc-exhorts-officials-to-aim-high/article8056883.ece\n|title=Human Development Index: DC exhorts officials to aim high\n|date=2 January 2016\n|access-date=18 February 2016\n|newspaper=The Hindu\n|author=Anil Kumar Sastry\n}}</ref><br />{{color|darkgreen|very high}}\n| blank1_name_sec2                = Literacy\n| blank1_info_sec2                = 94.03%<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_2_PR_Cities_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf\n|title=Cities having population 1 lakh and above, Census 2011\n|access-date=4 October 2015\n|publisher=censusindia.gov.in\n}}</ref>\n| website                         = {{URL|www.mangalurucity.mrc.gov.in}}\n}}\n\n'''Mangalore''', officially known as '''Mangaluru''', is the chief port city of the Indian state of [[Karnataka]]. It is located between the [[Arabian Sea]] and the [[Western Ghats]] mountain range about {{convert|352|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} west of [[Bangalore]], the state capital. Mangalore is the state's only city to have all four modes of transport\u2014air, road, rail and sea. The population of the [[urban agglomeration]] was 619,664&nbsp;{{as of|alt=according to the 2011|2011}}&nbsp;national census of India.\n\nThe city developed as a port in the Arabian Sea during ancient times; it has since developed into a major [[Ports in India|port of India]] that handles 75&nbsp;per&nbsp;cent of India's coffee and cashew exports, and is the country's seventh largest container port. Mangalore has been ruled by several major powers, including the [[Kadamba Dynasty|Kadambas]], [[Alupas]], [[Vijayanagar Empire]], [[Nayakas of Keladi|Keladi Nayaks]] and the Portuguese. The city was a source of contention between the [[British Raj|British]] and the [[Kingdom of Mysore]] rulers [[Hyder Ali]] and [[Tipu Sultan]], and was eventually annexed by the British in 1799. Mangalore remained part of the [[Madras Presidency]] until [[Partition of India|India's independence]] in 1947 and was unified with [[Mysore State]] (now called Karnataka) in 1956.\n\nMangalore is also the administrative headquarters of the [[Dakshina Kannada]] district, and is a commercial, industrial, educational, healthcare and startup hub. This city's International Airport is the second-largest airport in Karnataka. Mangalore City Corporation is responsible for the civic administration, which manages the 60&nbsp;wards of the city. The city's landscape is characterised by rolling hills, coconut palms, rivers and hard, red-clay-roofed buildings. India's first 3D&nbsp;planetarium with 8K&nbsp;resolution display is situated in this city. Mangalore is also included in the [[Smart Cities Mission]] list and is among the 100&nbsp;smart cities to be developed in India. The city has an average elevation of {{convert|22|m|foot|0|abbr=on}} above [[mean sea level]]. Mangalore has a tropical monsoon climate and is under the influence of the southwest monsoon.\n\n==Etymology==\n[[File:1652 Sanson Map of India - Geographicus - India-sanson-1652.jpg|thumb|left|1652 Sanson Map of India]]\nMangalore was named after the deity Mangaladevi, the presiding deity of the [[Mangaladevi Temple]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Kameshwar|first=G.|publisher=Rupa & Co.|title=Tulu tales: a soota chronicle|isbn=978-81-291-0427-4|year=2004|p=8}}</ref> or a synonym of [[Tara (Buddhism)|Tara]] Bhagvati of the [[Vajrayana]] [[Buddhist]] sect.<ref name=Sadasivan>{{cite book|last=Sadasivan|first=S.N.|title=A social history of India|year=2000|publisher=APH Pub. Corp.|isbn=81-7648-170-X|pages=207\u2013208}}</ref> According to local legend, a princess named Parimala or Premaladevi from Malabar<ref name=\"Swami2013\">{{cite book|author=Swami Atmashraddhananda|title=A Pilgrimage To Western Ghats Temples in Karnataka|year=2013|publisher=Sri Ramakrishna Math, Chennai|isbn=978-8178836157}}</ref> renounced her kingdom and became a disciple of [[Matsyendranath]], the founder of the [[Nath]] tradition.<ref name='namespast'>{{cite news|url = http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/New-names-invoke-a-hoary-past/articleshow/44873377.cms|title = New names invoke a hoary past|date = 19 October 2014|newspaper=The Times of India|access-date = 23 February 2015}}</ref> Having converted ''Premaladevi'' to the ''Nath'' sect, Matsyendranath renamed her ''Mangaladevi''.<ref name=\"Swami2013\"/><ref name='matsyendranath'>{{cite book\n|title = Census of India, 1971\n|publisher = Office of the Registrar General (Government of India)\n|year = 1973\n|pages=268\n|volume = Part 6, Issue 1}}</ref> She arrived in the area with Matsyendranath but had to settle near [[Bolar, Mangalore|Bolar]] in Mangalore because she fell ill on the way.<ref name='matsyendranath'/> When she died, the Mangaladevi temple at Bolar was consecrated in her honour by the local people.<ref name=\"Kudva1972\">{{cite book|author=Venkataraya Narayan Kudva|title=History of the Dakshinatya Saraswats|p=260|asin=B0000CQ1JW|year=1972|publisher=Samyukta Gowda Saraswata Sabha}}</ref><ref name=\"Swami2013\"/> The city got its name from the temple.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.deccanherald.com/sunday-herald/silence-shores-698661.html|title=A travel guide to coastal Karnataka|date=20 October 2018|accessdate=15 February 2020|newspaper=Deccan Herald}}</ref>\n\nOne of the earliest references to the city's name was made in 715&nbsp;CE by the [[Pandyan Kingdom|Pandyan]] King Chettian, who called the city ''Mangalapuram''.<ref name='namespast'/> The city and the coastal region were part of the Pandyan Kingdom.<ref name='namespast'/> According to [[K.V. Ramesh]], President of the Place Names Society of India, ''Mangaluru'' was first used in 1345&nbsp;CE during the Vijayanagar rule.<ref name=\"can\">{{cite news\n |url         = http://www.hindu.com/2007/07/18/stories/2007071855190700.htm\n |title       = Mangaluru: it has come a long way\n |access-date = 27 July 2008\n |first       = M.\n |last        = Raghuram\n |newspaper   = The Hindu\n |date        = 18 July 2007\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/66HqSfkYL?url=http://www.hindu.com/2007/07/18/stories/2007071855190700.htm\n |archivedate = 19 March 2012\n |df          = dmy\n}}</ref> Many ''shilashasanas'' (stones) of the Vijayanagar period refer the city as ''Mangalapura''.<ref name=\"can\"/> Before that, during the Alupa dynasty period, it was referred to as ''Mangalapura'' (''Mangala'' means 'auspicious').<ref name=\"can\"/> in Kannada language, the city is known as ''Mangaluru'', a reference to Mangaladevi (the suffix ''uru'' means town or city).<ref name=\"can\"/> During British rule from 1799, the [[Anglicization|anglicised]] version ''Mangalore'' became the official appellation.<ref name=\"can\"/> According to historian George M. Moraes, however, the word ''Mangalore'' is the [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] corruption of ''Mangaluru''.<ref name=\"far\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=qNHYAAAAMAAJ|title=The Christian Impact on South Kanara|first=Kranti K.|last= Farias|publisher=Church History Association of India|isbn=8175251255|year=1999}}</ref>{{rp|2}} The city's name appears on maps from as early as the 1652&nbsp;[[Nicolas Sanson|Sanson]] Map of India.<ref>{{cite web | title= 1652 Sanson Map of India |url =http://www.geographicus.com/P/AntiqueMap/India-sanson-1652|access-date=19 March 2012|publisher=Geographicus}}</ref>\n\nMangalore's diverse communities have different names for the city in their languages.<ref name=\"manynames\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thenewsminute.com/karnatakas/326|title=This city has six names in six languages|access-date=22 October 2017|date=6 November 2014|newspaper=The News Minute|author=Anisha Sheth}}</ref> In Tulu, the region's primary spoken language, the city is called ''Kudla'', meaning ''junction'' because it is situated at the confluence of the [[Netravati River|Netravati]] and [[Gurupura River|Gurupura]] rivers.<ref>{{cite news|url = https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/ALL-IN-A-NAME/articleshow/44871514.cms|title = ALL IN A NAME|accessdate = 23 February 2020|date=19 October 2014|newspaper=The Times of India}}</ref> In Konkani, Mangalore is referred to as ''Kodiyal'', while in [[Malayalam]], Mangalore is called ''Mangalapuram'' and the Beary name for the city is ''Maikala''.<ref>{{cite news|url = http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/filled-with-lore/article1418239.ece|title = Filled with lore|date = 9 June 2008|newspaper=The Hindu|access-date = 23 February 2015}}</ref> Mangalore was officially renamed to \"Mangaluru\" by the Karnataka government on 1&nbsp;November 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/bangalore-mysore-other-karnataka-cities-be-renamed-1-november-611683|title=Bangalore, Mysore, Other Karnataka Cities to be Renamed on 1 November|date=18 October 2014|accessdate=26 February 2020|newspaper=International Business Times|author=Mugdha Variyar}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{Main|History of Mangalore}}\n\n===Early and medieval history===\nMangalore's historical importance is highlighted by the many references to the city by foreign travellers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/content/175417/unearthing-rich-past.html|title=Unearthing a rich past|date=11 July 2011|access-date=17 July 2019|newspaper=Deccan Herald}}</ref> During the first century CE, the Roman historian [[Pliny the Elder]] made references to a place called \"Nitrias\" as an undesirable place for disembarkation because of the pirates who frequented its vicinity,<ref>{{cite book|title = Pliny the Elder, The Natural History|last = Bostock|first = John|publisher = Taylor and Francis|year = 1855|isbn = 1173878041 |pages = |chapter-url = http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.02.0137%3Abook%3D6%3Achapter%3D26#note-link33|chapter = 26 (Voyages to India)}}</ref> while Greek second-century historian [[Ptolemy]] referred to a place called \"Nitra\".<ref name='decayrevival'>{{cite book|title = Decay and Revival of Urban Centres in Medieval South India: (c. A.D. 600\u20131200)|last = Prasad|first = Om P.|publisher=Commonwealth Publishers|year = 1989|isbn = 9788171690060|pages = 163|volume = Volume 4 of Series in Indian history, art, and culture}}</ref> These remarks were probably referring to the Netravati River that flows through Mangalore.<ref name='decayrevival'/> In his sixth-century work ''[[Christian Topography]]'', [[Cosmas Indicopleustes]], a Greek monk, mentions Malabar as the chief seat of the pepper trade and ''Mangarouth'' (port of Mangalore) as one of the five pepper markets that exported pepper.<ref>{{cite book|last=Indicopleustes|first=Cosmas|title=Christian Topography|authorlink=Cosmas Indicopleustes|year=1897|series=11|isbn=1108012957|publisher=The Tertullian Project|pp=[https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.tertullian.org%2Ffathers%2Fcosmas_11_book11.htm&date=2012-03-19 358\u2013373]}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title = The Economic History of Ancient India|last = Das|first = Santosh Kumar|publisher = Genesis Publishing Pvt Ltd|year = 2006|isbn = 9788130704234|pages = 301}}</ref>\n\nMangalore is considered the heart of a distinct multi-linguistic cultural region, the homeland of the Tulu-speaking people.<!--HIDDEN EDITOR NOTE: Any inclusion of the Region needs consensus. Please don't add your Point of view--><ref name=\"Shatkin2013\">{{cite book|title=Contesting the Indian City: Global Visions and the Politics of the Local|author=Gavin Shatkin|date=14 August 2013|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-118-29584-7|chapter=Chapter 10 : Planning Mangalore: Garbage Collection in a Small Indian City}}</ref> In the third century BCE, the town formed part of the [[Maurya]] Empire, which was ruled by the Buddhist emperor [[Ashoka]] of [[Magadha]].<ref name=\"Swami2013\"/> From the third to the sixth century CE, the Kadamba dynasty, whose capital was based in [[Banavasi]] in [[North Canara]], ruled over the entire [[Kanara|Canara]] region as independent rulers.<ref name=\"Puttaswamaiah19802\">{{cite book|author=K. Puttaswamaiah|url=https://books.google.com/?id=tEAeAAAAIAAJ&q=puttaswamaiah+economic+development&dq=puttaswamaiah+economic+development|title=Economic Development of Karnataka: A Treatise in Continuity and Change|page=33|year=1980|publisher=Oxford & IBH}}</ref> From the middle of the seventh century to the end of the 14th&nbsp;century, the South Canara region was ruled by its native Alupa rulers,<ref name=\"sk\">{{cite book|last=Bhat|first=N. Shyam|title=South Kanara, 1799\u20131860: a study in colonial administration and regional response|publisher=Mittal Publications|year=1998|isbn=978-81-7099-586-9}}</ref>{{rp|17}}<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Mangalore/tulu-stone-inscription-in-veeranarayana-temple-belongs-to-1159-ad-historian/article26344575.ece|title=Tulu stone inscription in Veeranarayana temple belongs to 1159 A.D.: Historian|date=22 February 2019|access-date=18 July 2019|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref><ref name='tuluacademy'>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Mangalore/tulu-academy-to-publish-book-on-history-of-barakuru/article8039303.ece|title=Tulu academy to publish book on history of Barakuru |date=24 March 2016|access-date=18 July 2019|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref> who ruled over the region as feudatories of major regional dynasties like the [[Chalukya dynasty|Chalukyas of Badami]], [[Rashtrakutas]] of [[Malkheda|Manyakheta]], [[Western Chalukyas|Chalukyas of Kalyani]] and [[Hoysalas]] of [[Halebidu (town)|Dwarasamudra]].<ref name=\"sk\"/> During the 1130s&nbsp;and&nbsp;1140s, during the reign of the Alupa king Kavi Alupendra (1110\u20131160), the city was home to the [[Tunisian people|Tunisian]] Jewish merchant [[Abraham Ben Yiju]].<ref>{{harvnb|Ghosh|2002|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=QQHp9wsWaZcC&pg=PA189&dq=&sig=ACfU3U1d2AKJLTdQT1Hs-VurHOe06DStCg#PPA189,M1 189]|Ref=9}}</ref> The [[Moroccan people|Moroccan]] traveller [[Ibn Battuta]], who visited Mangalore in 1342, referred to it as ''Manjarur'' and stated the town was situated on a large estuary called the ''Estuary of the wolf'', which was the greatest estuary in the country of Malabar.<ref>{{harvnb|Lee|1829|loc=[https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.columbia.edu%2Fitc%2Fmealac%2Fpritchett%2F00generallinks%2Fibnbatuta%2F07china2.html%23malabar&date=2012-03-19 Perils and detours in Malabar]|Ref=17}}</ref><ref name=\"Doddamane1993\">{{cite book|author=A. Wahab Doddamane|title=Muslims in Dakshina Kannada: A Historical Study up to 1947 and Survey of Recent Developments|year=1993|publisher=Green Words Publication}}</ref>{{rp|30}} By 1345, the Vijayanagara rulers brought the region under their control.<ref name=\"sk\" />{{rp|17}}\n\nDuring the Vijayanagara period (1345\u20131550), South Canara was divided into Mangalore and Barkur ''rajyas'' (provinces), and two governors were appointed to look after each of them from Mangalore and [[Barkur]].<ref name=\"sk\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mangaluru/Rare-inscription-of-Vijayanarar-discovered/articleshow/6447579.cms|title=Rare inscription of Vijayanagar discovered|date=27 August 2010|access-date=18 July 2019|newspaper=The Times of India|author=K Mohanachandran Nambiar}}</ref> Often a single governor ruled over both Mangalore and Barkur ''rajyas'', and when the authority passed to the Keladi rulers (1550\u20131763), they had a governor at Barkur only.<ref name=\"sk\" />{{rp|19}} In 1448, [[Abd-al-Razz\u0101q Samarqand\u012b|Abdur Razzaq]], the Persian ambassador of [[Shahrukh Mirza|Sultan Shah Rukh]] of [[Samarkand]], visited Mangalore ''en route'' to the Vijayanagara court.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Sewell |first=Robert |title=The Project Gutenberg E-text of A Forgotten Empire: Vijayanagar; A Contribution to the History of India|url=https://my.eng.utah.edu/~banerjee/Ebooks/Vijayanagar.pdf|publisher=[[Project Gutenberg]]|page=46|access-date=18 July 2019|date = July 2002}}</ref><ref name=\"Doddamane1993\"/>{{rp|31}} The Italian traveller [[Ludovico di Varthema]], who visited India in 1506, said he saw nearly sixty ships laden with rice ready to sail from the port of Mangalore.<ref name=\"sk\"/>{{rp|20}}\n\n===Foundation and early modern history===\n[[File:Lopo Vaz de Sampaio (Archaeological Survey of India, Goa).png|thumb|left|upright|[[Lopo Vaz de Sampaio]], Viceroy of [[Portuguese India]], established Portuguese rule in Mangalore in 1526,<ref name=\"Wenger2017\">{{cite book|author=Estefania Wenger|title=Tipu Sultan: A Biography|year=2017|publisher=Alpha Editions|isbn=9789386367440}}</ref> which lasted until 1695.<ref name=\"Muthanna 1977\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=bFq-bwAACAAJ|last=Muthanna|first=I. M.|title=Karnataka, History, Administration & Culture|year=1977|publisher=Lotus Printers|p=235}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Mangalorefort1783.jpg|thumb|right|alt=A fort with two-tiered ramparts and many bastions rises above the far bank of a river. Some human settlements are visible nearby.| A pen and ink drawing of Mangalore Fort made in 1783, after it had been taken over by the British East India Company]]\n[[File:Light House at Tagore park.jpg|thumb|right|upright|The tower at [[Light House Hill]], [[Hampankatta]], served as a lookout for the [[British Empire|British]].<ref>{{cite news\n |url         = http://www.hindu.com/mp/2005/06/18/stories/2005061800910200.htm\n |title       = Feeling on top of the world\n |access-date = 22 August 2008\n |first       = M.\n |last        = Raghuram\n |newspaper   = [[The Hindu]]\n |date        = 18 June 2005\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/66BGA0KPU?url=http://www.hindu.com/mp/2005/06/18/stories/2005061800910200.htm\n |archivedate = 15 March 2012\n |df          = dmy\n}}</ref>|alt=]]\nIn 1498, European influence in Mangalore began when the Portuguese explorer [[Vasco da Gama]] landed at the nearby [[St Mary's Island, Karnataka|St Mary's Islands]].<ref>{{cite news\n |url         = http://www.thehindubusinessline.in/life/2002/09/16/stories/2002091600170300.htm\n |title       = Where rocks tell a tale\n |first       = J.\n |last        = Kamath\n |date        = 16 September 2002\n |access-date = 8 July 2008\n |newspaper   = The Hindu Business Line\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/65qXkyc56?url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.in/life/2002/09/16/stories/2002091600170300.htm\n |archivedate = 1 March 2012\n |df          = dmy\n}}</ref> The Portuguese acquired many commercial interests in Canara in the 16th century.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mangaluru/abbakka-utsav-2019-to-be-held-under-supervision-of-dc/articleshow/68203620.cms|title=Abbakka Utsav 2019 to be held under supervision of DC|date=28 February 2019|access-date=18 July 2019|newspaper=The Times of India|author=Vinobha K T}}</ref> [[Krishnadevaraya]] (1509\u20131529), the ruler of the Vijaynagara empire maintained a friendly relationship with the Portuguese,<ref name=\"Jayapalan2001\">{{cite book|author=N. Jayapalan|title=History of India From 1206 to 1773|year=2001|publisher=Atlantic Publishers & Distributors|isbn=978-8171569151|p=84}}</ref> whose trade slowly grew and they strove to destroy the coastal Arab and [[Moplah]] trade.<ref name=\"sk\" /> In 1524, Vasco da Gama ordered the blockading of rivers after he heard the Muslim merchants of [[Calicut]] had agents at Mangalore and [[Basrur]].<ref name=\"sk\" /> In 1526, the Portuguese under the viceroyship of Lopo Vaz de Sampaio took possession of Mangalore.<ref name=\"Wenger2017\"/> The coastal trade passed into Portuguese hands.<ref name=\"sk\" />{{rp|20}} In 1550, the Vijayanagara ruler [[Sadashiva Raya]] entrusted to Sadashiv Nayaka of Keladi with administering the coastal region of Canara.<ref name=\"sk\" /> By 1554, he established political authority over South Canara.<ref name=\"Shastry2000\">{{cite book|author=Bhagamandala Seetharama Shastry|title=Goa-Kanara Portuguese relations 1498-1763|year=2000|publisher=Concept Publishing Company|isbn=9788170228486|p=8}}</ref>\n\nAfter the disintegration of the Vijaynagara Empire in 1565, the rulers of Keladi attained greater power in dealing with the coastal Canara region.<ref name=\"sk\" />{{rp|27}} They continued the Vijayanagara administrative system<ref name=\"sk\" /> and the provinces of Mangalore and Barkur continued to exist.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.deccanherald.com/content/336375/remains-another-day.html |title=Remains of another day |access-date=18 July 2019 |newspaper=Deccan Herald |date=3 June 2013|author=Soumya Narayan Achari}}</ref><ref name=\"tuluacademy\" /> The governor of Mangalore also acted as the governor of the Keladi army in his province.<ref name=\"sk\" />{{rp|30}} The Italian traveller [[Pietro Della Valle]] visited here in 1623\u20131624.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=QhLwrzK4Hq8C Viaggi di Pietro Della Valle il pellegrino], Parte terza, by Pietro Della Valle and Mario Schipano, Rome (1663), pages 222-224.</ref> In 1695, Arabs burnt the town in retaliation to Portuguese restrictions on Arab trade.<ref name=\"Muthanna 1977\"/>\n\nIn 1763, Hyder Ali, the ''de facto'' ruler of the Kingdom of Mysore, conquered Mangalore,<ref name=\"sch64\">\n{{harvnb|South Kanara District Gazetteer|1973|p=62|Ref=sch}}</ref> which was brought under his administration until 1767. Mangalore was ruled by the [[Honourable East India Company|British East India Company]] from 1767&nbsp;to 1783,<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{harvnb|Thornton|1859|p=[https://archive.org/details/historybritishe04thorgoog 114]|Ref=27}}</ref> but Hyder Ali's son Tipu Sultan subsequently took it from their control in 1783 and renamed it \"Jalalabad\".<ref>{{harvnb|Thornton|1859|p=[https://archive.org/details/historybritishe04thorgoog 170]|Ref=27}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Lal|2002|p=22}}</ref> The [[Second Anglo-Mysore War|Second Anglo\u2013Mysore War]] ended with the signing of the [[Treaty of Mangalore]] by Tipu Sultan and the British East India Company on 11&nbsp;March 1784.<ref>{{harvnb|Forrest|1887|pp=314\u2013316|Ref=8}}</ref> After the defeat of Tipu at the [[Fourth Anglo-Mysore War|Fourth Anglo\u2013Mysore War]], the city remained under British control, headquartering South Canara district under the Madras Presidency.<ref name=\"can\" /><ref name=\"Thornton\">{{harvnb|Townsend|1867|p=[https://archive.org/details/manualofdatesdic00townrich/page/628 628]|Ref=271}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Riddick|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=V2nGnWXV7coC&pg=PA28&dq=&sig=ACfU3U1AqhfzPUctT1n1lmbLKqrtzEu7qw#PPA28,M1 28]|Ref=23}}</ref>\n\n[[Francis Buchanan]], a Scottish physician who visited Mangalore in 1801, said the city was a prosperous port with plentiful trade.<ref name=\"jp0687\">{{harvnb|Prabhu|1999|p=152}}</ref> The main commodity of export was rice; it went to [[Muscat, Oman|Muscat]], [[Bombay]], [[Goa]] and [[Malabar district|Malabar]].<ref name=\"sk\" /> ''Supari'' ([[Areca nut|Betel-nut]]) was exported to Bombay, [[Surat]] and [[Kutch]].<ref name=\"sk\" /> [[Sandalwood]] and [[black pepper]] were exported to Bombay.<ref name=\"sk\" />\n\nLocal capital was mainly invested in land and money lending, leading to the regional development of banking because the British colonial government did not support industrialisation there.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Mangalore/dakshina-kannada-to-lose-banking-jewel/article26690322.ece|title=Dakshina Kannada to lose banking jewel|access-date=17 July 2019|newspaper=The Hindu|date=31 March 2019}}</ref> After European missionaries arrived in the early 19th&nbsp;century, educational institutions and modern industries modelled on European ones were developed in the region.<ref>{{cite news\n |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Mangalore/175-glorious-years-for-Basel-Mission-Press/article16762961.ece\n |title=175 glorious years for Basel Mission Press\n |access-date=16 February 2017\n |newspaper=The Hindu\n |date=5 December 2016 \n}}</ref> The opening of the [[Lutheran]] Swiss [[Basel Mission]] in 1834&nbsp;was an important step towards industrialisation.<ref>{{cite news\n |url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/32972/175th-anniversary-basel-mission-mangalore.html\n |title=175th anniversary of Basel Mission in Mangalore, Udupi\n |access-date=16 February 2017\n |newspaper=Deccan Herald\n |date=28 October 2009\n}}</ref> Missionaries set up printing presses, textile mills and factories that made [[Mangalore tiles]].<ref name=\"Shatkin2013\" /> When Canara (part of the Madras Presidency until this time) was split into North Canara and South Canara in 1859, Mangalore became the headquarters of South Canara,<ref name=\"Bhat2001\"/>{{rp|5}} which remained under Madras Presidency while in 1862, North Canara was transferred to the [[Bombay Presidency]].<ref name=\"Bhat2001\">{{cite book|author=N. Shyam Bhat|title=Judiciary and Police in Early Colonial South Kanara, 1799\u20131862|year=2001|publisher=Mittal Publications|isbn=978-81-7099-820-4}}</ref>{{rp|6}}\n\n===Later modern and contemporary history===\nOn 23&nbsp;May 1866, a municipal council for Mangalore with responsibility for civic amenities and urban planning was mandated by the Madras Town Improvement Act (1865).<ref name=\"far\"/>{{rp|178}} The Italian [[Jesuits]] who arrived in the city in 1878, played an important role in the city's education, economy, health and social welfare.<ref>{{cite news|url = http://www.daijiworld.com/news/news_disp.asp?n_id=211432|title = Last of Italian Jesuits in Mangalore dies in his homeland|last = Monteiro|first = John B|date = 8 January 2014|newspaper=Daijiworld|access-date = 1 March 2015}}</ref> Mangalore was linked to the [[Southern Railway (India)|Southern Railway]] in 1907 and the subsequent proliferation of motor vehicles in India further increased trade and communication between the city and the rest of the country.<ref name=\"so\">{{cite news\n |url         = http://www.hindu.com/2007/10/29/stories/2007102958510300.htm\n |title       = Mangalore was once the starting point of India's longest rail route\n |date        = 29 October 2007\n |access-date = 19 March 2008\n |newspaper=The Hindu\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/66BFugtWc?url=http://www.hindu.com/2007/10/29/stories/2007102958510300.htm\n |archivedate = 15 March 2012\n |df          = dmy\n |author=Sudipto Mondal\n}}</ref> Mangalore was a major source of educated workers to [[Bombay]], Bangalore and the Middle East by the early 20th century.<ref name=\"Shatkin2013\" />\n\nThe [[States Reorganisation Act]] (1956) led to Mangalore being incorporated into the newly created Mysore State, which was later renamed Karnataka.<ref name=\"sorg1956\">{{cite web|url=http://www.commonlii.org/in/legis/num_act/sra1956250/|title=States Reorganisation Act 1956|access-date=1 July 2008|publisher=Commonwealth Legal Information Institute|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516123014/http://www.commonlii.org/in/legis/num_act/sra1956250/|archive-date=16 May 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"skdg\">{{cite book|year=1973|url=https://books.google.com/?id=-6j8tgAACAAJ|title=South Kanara District Gazetteer|series=Karnataka State Gazetteer|volume=12|publisher=Gazetteer Department ([[Government of Karnataka]])}}</ref>{{rp|415}} Mangalore is the fourth-largest city of Karnataka in terms of population and the seventh-largest port of India, giving the state access to the Arabian Sea coastline.<ref name=\"Shatkin2013\" /><ref name='container-port'>{{cite news |url=https://www.daijiworld.com/news/newsDisplay.aspx?newsID=539779|title=Container tracking operations launched at New Mangalore Port|date=22 November 2018|accessdate=2 March 2020|newspaper=Daijiworld}}</ref> Between 1970 and 1980, Mangalore experienced significant growth with the opening of [[New Mangalore Port]] in 1974&nbsp;and commissioning of Mangalore Chemicals & Fertilizers Limited in 1976.<ref name=\"Panda1991\">{{cite book|author=Damodar Panda|title=Cargo Handling in the Major Ports of India|year=1991|publisher=Minerva Associates (Publications)|isbn=978-81-85195-33-9|p=30}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url = http://www.frontline.in/static/html/fl2419/stories/20071005507310600.htm|title = Industrial leap|last = Sharma|first = Ravi|date =|journal = [[Frontline (magazine)|Frontline]]|doi = |pmid = |access-date = 1 March 2015|issue = 19 ( 22 Sep. \u2013 5 October 2007)|volume = 24|series = |publisher = [[The Hindu]]}}</ref> The late 20th&nbsp;and early 21st&nbsp;centuries saw Mangalore develop as a commercial and petrochemical hub.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.deccanherald.com/state/cbi-books-mrpl-engineer-713765.html|title=CBI books MRPL engineer|date=18 January 2019|accessdate=23 February 2020|newspaper=Deccan Herald|author=Ambarish Bhat}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/todays-paper/tp-others/tp-states/Strategic-oil-reserves-to-come-directly-under-Govt/article20203878.ece|title=Strategic oil reserves to come directly under Govt|date=2 April 2006|accessdate=23 February 2020|newspaper=The Hindu Business Line|author=Richa Mishra}}</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Ullal Bridge Mangalore.JPG|thumb|left|Sunset at [[Netravati Bridge]]]]\n\nMangalore is located on the western coast of India at {{Coord|12.87|N|74.88|E}} in Dakshina Kannada district, Karnataka state.<ref name=\"Mangalore, India Page\">{{cite web\n|publisher=Falling Rain Genomics, Inc|url=http://www.fallingrain.com/world/IN/19/Mangalore.html|title=Mangalore, India Page\n|access-date=19 March 2008}}</ref> It has an average elevation of {{convert|22|m|foot|0|abbr=on}} above mean sea level.<ref>{{cite web\n |publisher   = [[Indian Institute of Tropical Meteorology]] ([[Pune]])\n |url         = http://envis.tropmet.res.in/rainfall_stations.htm\n |title       = Rainfall Stations in India\n |access-date = 27 July 2008\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/5tcfc0JvM?url=http://envis.tropmet.res.in/rainfall_stations.htm\n |archivedate = 20 October 2010\n |url-status     = dead\n |df          = dmy\n}}</ref> The city is the administrative headquarters of Dakshina Kannada district and is the state's largest coastal urban centre.<ref name=\"urb\">{{cite book | last1 = Rao | first1 = P. S. N. | title = Urban governance and management: Indian initiatives | date = January 2006 | publisher=Indian Institute of Public Administration in association with Kanishka Publishers, Distributors|page=402|isbn=978-81-7391-801-8}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Mangalore Tourist Map.png|thumb|A schematic map showing the tourist places in Mangalore city]]\nMangalore is bounded by the Arabian Sea to its west and by the Western Ghats to its east.<ref name=\"Mangalore, India Page\"/> As a municipal entity, the city spans {{convert|184|km2|sqmi|2|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"area-info\"/> The Netravati and Gurupura rivers encircle the city; the Gurupura flows around the north and the Netravati flows around the south of the city.<ref name=\"vegetation-info\">{{cite web |url=http://cgwb.gov.in/District_Profile/karnataka/DAKSHINA_KANNADA.pdf|title=Ground water information booklet \u2013 Dakshina Kannada district, Karnataka|access-date=19 February 2017 }}</ref> The rivers form an estuary in the south-western region of the city, from where they flow into the Arabian Sea.<ref name=\"MCCwater\">{{harvnb|Mangalore City Corporation|p=38|Ref=7}}</ref> Coconut, [[Arecaceae|palm]] and [[ashoka]] trees comprise the primary vegetation of the city.<ref name=\"vegetation-info\"/>\n\nThe city's [[topography]] consists of a [[plain]] that stretches up to {{convert|30|km|mi|2|abbr=on}} from the coast and undulating, hilly terrain towards the east near the Western Ghats.<ref>{{cite book | title=Mausam: quarterly journal of meteorology, hydrology & geophysics, Volume 56, Issue 1 | publisher=[[India Meteorological Department]]| year=2005 | page=76}}</ref> The local geology is characterised by hard [[laterite]] in hilly tracts and sandy soil along the seashore.<ref name=\"urb\"/> The [[Geological Survey of India]] has identified Mangalore as a moderately earthquake-prone urban centre and categorised the city in the Seismic III Zone.<ref>{{cite map\n|publisher=[[Geological Survey of India]]|url=http://gcmd.nasa.gov/records/GCMD_GSI_BHUJ_SEISMIC_ZONES_MAP.html|title=Seismic zoning map of India|access-date=20 July 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Climate===\nUnder the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]], Mangalore has a [[tropical monsoon climate]] and is under the direct influence of the Arabian Sea branch of the [[southwest monsoon]].<ref name=\"climatetype\">{{cite journal |author=Subrahmanyam, V. P. |title=Some aspects of water balance in the tropical monsoon climates of India |journal=Hydrology of Humid Tropical Regions with Particular Reference to the Hydrological Effects of Agriculture and Forestry Practice (Proceedings of the Hamburg Symposium, August 1983) |volume=140 |publisher=[[International Association of Hydrological Sciences]] (IAHS) |url=http://www.cig.ensmp.fr/~iahs/redbooks/a140/iahs_140_0325.pdf |pages=327\u2013328 |access-date=8 July 2008\n|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081003062744/http://www.cig.ensmp.fr/~iahs/redbooks/a140/iahs_140_0325.pdf |archivedate=3 October 2008}}</ref> It receives about 95&nbsp;per&nbsp;cent of its total annual rainfall between May to October but remains extremely dry from December to March.<ref name=\"climatetype\"/> The average annual [[precipitation]] in Mangalore is {{convert|3796.9|mm|in|0}}.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.imd.gov.in/ims/pdf/climateimp.pdf\n |title=IMD \u2013 Monthly mean maximum & minimum temperature and total rainfall based upon 1901 \u2013 2000 data (Page 42)\n |access-date=11 December 2014\n |publisher=India Meteorological Department\n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116015803/http://www.imd.gov.in/ims/pdf/climateimp.pdf\n |archivedate=16 January 2013\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n|url= http://worldweather.wmo.int/en/city.html?cityId=1607\n|title= World Weather Information Service \u2013 Climatological Information for Mangalore, India\n|access-date=30 January 2015\n|publisher=[[World Meteorological Organization]]}}</ref> Humidity is approximately 75&nbsp;per&nbsp;cent on average and peaks during June, July and August.<ref name=\"shri\">{{harvnb|Shrihari|2007|pp=5\u20136}}</ref> The maximum average humidity is 93&nbsp;per&nbsp;cent in July and average minimum humidity is 56&nbsp;per&nbsp;cent in January.<ref name=\"shri\"/>\n\nMangalore experiences moderate to gusty winds during day time and gentle winds at night.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Balakrishna\n|first=K. M.|author2=Narayana, Y |author3=Kumari, Anitha |title=Meteorological Measurements of Mangalore Region for ARMEX Programme (Observations and Data Analysis)|url=http://www.nio.org/past_events/ARMEX/presentations/P2.pdf|publisher=Department of Physics ([[Mangalore University]])|page=26|access-date=25 March 2008| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080410145013/http://www.nio.org/past_events/ARMEX/presentations/P2.pdf| archivedate = 10 April 2008}}</ref> The driest and least humid months are from December to February.<ref name=\"Wbase\">{{cite web\n|publisher=Weatherbase\n|url=http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather.php3?s=48234&refer=&units=metric\n|title=Mangalore, India\n|access-date=19 March 2008}}</ref> During this period, temperatures during the day stay below {{convert|34|\u00b0C|\u00b0F|0}} and drop to about {{convert|19|\u00b0C|\u00b0F|0}} at night.<ref>{{cite web\n| url = https://weather-and-climate.com/average-monthly-Rainfall-Temperature-Sunshine,Mangalore,India\n| title = Average minimum and maximum temperature over the year for Mangalore, India\n| access-date = 10 July 2017\n| publisher = Weather and Climate}}</ref> The lowest temperature recorded at [[Panambur]] is {{convert|15.6|\u00b0C|\u00b0F|0}} on 8&nbsp;January 1992 and at Bajpe it is {{convert|15.9|\u00b0C|\u00b0F|0}} on 19&nbsp;November 1974.<ref name=\"imd-weather\">{{cite web\n|publisher=IMD, Inc|url=http://www.imdbangalore.gov.in/mchistory.pdf#15|title=Weather services to Karnataka state delivered by IMD\n|access-date=17 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[India Meteorological Department]] (IMD), the temperature in Mangalore has never reached {{convert|40|\u00b0C|\u00b0F|0}}.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=Daijiworld |url=http://www.daijiworld.com/news/news_disp.asp?n_id=224013 |title=Mangalore: Temperature in coast never touched 40\u00b0 C \u2013 IMD |access-date=27 September 2015 |date=20 March 2014|author=Shreyas H S}}</ref> The highest temperature ever recorded in Mangalore is {{convert|38.1|\u00b0C|\u00b0F|0}} on 13&nbsp;March 1985.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=IMD, Inc |url=http://www.imdpune.gov.in/Temp_Extremes/histext2010.pdf#33 |title=Ever Recorded Maximum Temperature, Minimum Temperature and 24 Hours Heaviest Rainfall up to 2010 |access-date = 24 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6GmnoaB0m?url=http://www.imdpune.gov.in/Temp_Extremes/histext2010.pdf |archivedate = 21 May 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"imd-weather\"/> The summer gives way to the monsoon season, when the city experiences the highest precipitation of all urban centres in India due to the influence of the Western Ghats.<ref name=\"UNESCO World Heritage Centre\">{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/2103/|title= Western Ghats (sub cluster nomination)|access-date=27 July 2008 |publisher=[[UNESCO]] World Heritage Centre}}</ref> The rains subside in September but there is occasional rainfall in October.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Mishra, A. K. |author2=Gnanaseelan, C. |author3=Seetaramayya, P. |url=http://www.iisc.ernet.in/currsci/aug252004/475.pdf |date=25 August 2004 |journal=[[Current Science]] |volume=87 |title=A study of rainfall along the west coast of India in relation to low level jet and air\u2013sea interactions over the Arabian Sea |issue=4|page=483 |publisher=Current Science Association |access-date=21 March 2008}}</ref> The highest rainfall recorded in a 24-hour period is {{convert|330.8|mm|in|0|abbr=on}} on 22&nbsp;June 2003.<ref name=\"imd-weather\"/> In 1994, Mangalore recorded the highest annual rainfall at {{convert|5018.52|mm|in|0|abbr=on}}.<ref name= tutiempo >{{cite web|url=http://www.tutiempo.net/en/Climate/Mangalore_Bajpe/432840.htm |title = TuTiempo \u2013 Mangalore climate from 1973 to 2014 |access-date=27 December 2014 |publisher=Tutiempo}}</ref>\n{{Weather box\n|collapsed = y\n| location           = Mangalore, India\n| metric first       = yes\n| single line        = y\n| Jan record high C = 36.3\n| Feb record high C = 37.8\n| Mar record high C = 38.1\n| Apr record high C = 36.6\n| May record high C = 36.7\n| Jun record high C = 34.4\n| Jul record high C = 35.5\n| Aug record high C = 32.2\n| Sep record high C = 34.6\n| Oct record high C 