 Adebowale}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Charmeefit", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Omotunde_Adebowale_David"}
{"title_page": "Rudaali", "text_new": "{{short description|1993 Indian Hindi-language film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Rudaali\n| image          = Rudaali.jpg\n| caption        = DVD cover\n| director       = [[Kalpana Lajmi]]\n| producer       = Ravi Gupta<br />Ravi Malik\n| writer         = [[Mahasweta Devi]] (story)<br />[[Gulzar]]\n| narrator       =\n| starring       = [[Dimple Kapadia]]<br />[[Raj Babbar]]<br />[[Raakhee]]<br />[[Amjad Khan (actor)|Amjad Khan]]\n| music          = [[Bhupen Hazarika]]\n| cinematography = [[Santosh Sivan]]<br /> Dharam Gulati\n| released       = {{Film date|1993|6|18|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 128 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = Hindi\n| budget         =\n}}\n'''''Rudaali''''' is a [[Bollywood films of 1993|1993]] Indian [[Hindi]]-language [[drama film]] directed by [[Kalpana Lajmi]], based on the short story written by famous [[Bengali people|Bengali]] author [[Mahasweta Devi]].<ref name=\"QuintLegacy\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thequint.com/india/2016/07/28/of-mourning-and-revolution-mahasweta-devis-legacy-on-the-screen-rudaali-hazaar-chaurasi-ki-maa|title=Mourning and Revolution: Mahasweta Devi's Legacy on the Screen|date=28 July 2016|website=The Quint|author=Maanvi|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/celebrities/story/mahasweta-devi-death-dead-famous-films-rudaali-hazaar-chaurasi-ki-maa-331939-2016-07-28|title=Mahasweta Devi, RIP: Rudaali to Sunghursh, 5 films that immortalise the author's works|first=Devarsi|last=Ghosh|date=28 July 2016|website=India Today|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> The film was selected as the Indian entry for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]] at the [[66th Academy Awards]], but was not accepted as a nominee.<ref>Margaret Herrick Library, Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences</ref><ref name=\"Variety\">{{cite journal | last = Frook | first = John Evan | title = Acad inks Cates, unveils foreign-language entries | journal = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=30 November 1993| url = http://www.variety.com/article/VR116185.html?categoryid=13&cs=1 | accessdate =25 August 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe film is set in a small village in [[Rajasthan]], [[India]]. It tells the story of a woman named Shanichari, who was abandoned by her mother shortly after her father's death. Bad fortune follows her throughout her life.\n\n==Cultural background==\nThe title is a reference to a custom in certain areas of Rajasthan where women of a lower caste are hired as [[professional mourners]] upon the death of upper-caste males. These women are referred to as a \"rudaali\" (roo-dah-lee), literally translated as \"female weeper\" or \"weeping woman\". Their job is to publicly express grief of family members who are not permitted to display emotion due to social status.<ref name=\"UIowa\">{{cite web| title = Rudaali| url = http://www.uiowa.edu/~incinema/Rudaali.html| work = University of Iowa| accessdate = 1 September 2014| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131019024024/http://www.uiowa.edu/~incinema/Rudaali.html| archivedate = 19 October 2013| df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nThe story begins with Ram Avtar, the zamindar ({{trans|landlord}}) of Barna (a village in the desert) realizing his imminent death, and the fact that none of his relatives would mourn him. He thus requests for the services of a famous rudaali named Bhikni ([[Rakhee Gulzar|Rakhee]]), to mourn for him once he dies. Bhikni ends up staying with the widow Shanichari, who lives within the Thakur's compound. As they both begin to bond, Shanichari tells Bhikni her life's story, which is revealed to us in flashbacks.\n\nShanichari was born on a ''Shanichar'' (Saturday), which is concerned to be an [[ill omen]]ed day, ruled by the planet ''Shani'' ([[Saturn]]) in astrology. Shanichari is blamed by the villagers for everything bad that happens around her - starting from her father's death, to her mother Peewli's running off to join a folk theatre troupe. While still young, Shanichari is married off to Ganju, a drunkard, who ends up dying due to a plague at a village fair. Her only support is her son, Budhua, whom she loves very much. However, he likes to roam around aimlessly, just like Peewli did.\n\nMeanwhile, the Thakur's son Lakshman Singh reveals that he likes her and offers her a job at the Thakur's ''[[haveli]]''. She then serves under his wife, who has been spoiled but is secluded from others. Lakshman tries to teach Shanichari to empower herself and understand her rights, and encourages her to \"look up\" into his eyes when speaking to him. One night, after Shanichari's singing performance at the ''haveli'', he gifts her a house of her own, along with two acres of land.\n\nSoon, the adult Budhua brings home a wife, Mungri, who is a young prostitute pregnant with his child. However, the couple keeps fighting, and one day in a fit of rage, Mungri [[Abortion|aborts]] the child. Budhua, upset, runs away from home, leaving his mother all alone. It is revealed that throughout her hardships, Shanichari had never shed a tear.\n\nOne night, Bhikni is called to the neighbouring village to meet Bhimdata. The Thakur passes away a few hours later. Lakshman Singh and Shanichari are then seen bidding farewell to each other as Singh plans to leave the village after his father's demise. They are interrupted by a messenger from Bhimdata, who reveals that Bhikni succumbed to the plague, and in her last few minutes requested that Shanichari be told that she was her mother, Peewli. Shanichari then begins to weep profusely, and takes over as the new rudaali, crying at the Thakur's funeral.<ref name=\"UIowa\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url= https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/1809394439/details# |title=Rudaali Production Details |website=Yahoo! Movies |access-date=15 January 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110522110439/http://movies.yahoo.com/movie/1809394439/details# |archive-date= 22 May 2011 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Dimple Kapadia]] as Shanichari\n* [[Amjad Khan (actor)|Amjad Khan]] as Ram Avtar, the zamindaar\n* [[Raj Babbar]] as Lakshman Singh, Ram Avtar's son\n* [[Rakhee Gulzar|Rakhee]] as Bhikni, a rudaali\n* [[Raghubir Yadav]] as an adult Budhua\n* [[Sushmita Mukherjee]] as Mungri, Budhua's wife\n* [[Mita Vashisht]]\n* [[Manohar Singh]]\n* Minaaz\n\n==Awards and honours==\n* Dimple Kapadia won the [[National Film Award for Best Actress]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/entertainment/dimple-kapadia-reacts-to-health-rumours-im-alive-and-kicking-2133795|title=Dimple Kapadia Reacts To Health Rumours: 'I'm Alive And Kicking'|website=NDTV.com|date=17 November 2019|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> and the [[Filmfare Awards]] Best Performance Critics Award.<ref name=\"ToIAwards\">{{Citation|title=Rudaali Awards: List of Awards won by Hindi movie Rudaali|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/movie-details/rudaali/movieawards/61335648.cms|work=Times of India|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Samir Chanda]] won the [[National Film Award for Best Art Direction]].<ref name=\"ToIAwards\" />\n* [[Simple Kapadia]] and Mala Dey won the [[National Film Award (India)|National Film Award]] for Best Costume Design.<ref name=\"ToIAwards\" />\n* Bhupen Hazarika was awarded the Best Music Director National Award in 1993.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/inspiring-lives/bhupen-hazarika-the-bard-of-brahmaputra/story-8IkggPd3dEu49dZN9D1sHJ.html|title=Bhupen Hazarika: The Bard of Brahmaputra|date=17 September 2019|website=Hindustan Times|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n* The film was India's official entry to the [[66th Academy Awards]] for the Best Foreign Language Film category.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/photogallery/movies/all-the-indian-films-that-were-indias-official-entry-to-the-academy-awards-2360805.html|title=Before Gully Boy, these Indian films were sent to the Academy Award for Best International Feature Film Category|date=10 February 2020|website=News18|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Amjad Khan (actor)|Amjad Khan]] died before the film was released, and the film is dedicated to him.<ref name=\"QuintLegacy\" />\n\n==Soundtrack==\nThe film has music by folk musician [[Bhupen Hazarika]].\n\n{{Track listing\n| all_music       = Bhupen Hazarika\n| all_lyrics      = [[Gulzar]]\n| extra_column    = Artist(s)\n| title1          = Dil Hoom Hoom Kare (Part-1)\n| extra1          = [[Lata Mangeshkar]]\n| note1            = Raga: [[Bhoopali]]\n| title2          = Dil Hoom Hoom Kare (Part-2)\n| extra2          = Bhupen Hazarika\n| note2            = Raga: Bhoopali\n| title3          = Jhuti Mooti Mitwa\n| extra3          = Lata Mangeshkar\n| note3            = Raga: [[Vrindavani sarang]]\n| title4          = Samay O Dhire Chalo (Part-1)\n| extra4          = [[Asha Bhosle]]\n| note4            = Raga: [[Bhimpalasi]]\n| title5          = Samay O Dhire Chalo (Part-2)\n| extra5          = Bhupen Hazarika\n| note5            = Raga: Bhimpalasi\n| title6          = Moula O Moula\n| extra6          = Bhupen Hazarika\n| note6            = \n| title7          = Samay O Dhire Chalo (Part-3)\n| extra7          = Lata Mangeshkar\n| note7            = Raga: Bhimpalasi\n}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of submissions to the 66th Academy Awards for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n* [[List of Indian submissions for the Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0108001|title=Rudaali}}\n\n{{Indian submission for Academy Awards}}\n\n[[Category:1993 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:1990s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:1990s drama films]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Actress National Award-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films set in Rajasthan]]\n[[Category:Films based on short fiction]]\n[[Category:Films about women in India]]\n[[Category:Films about poverty in India]]\n[[Category:Death customs]]\n[[Category:Films whose production designer won the Best Production Design National Film Award]]\n[[Category:Films that won the Best Costume Design National Film Award]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1993 Indian Hindi-language film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Rudaali\n| image          = Rudaali.jpg\n| caption        = DVD cover\n| director       = [[Kalpana Lajmi]]\n| producer       = Ravi Gupta<br />Ravi Malik\n| writer         = [[Mahasweta Devi]] (story)<br />[[Gulzar]]\n| narrator       =\n| starring       = [[Dimple Kapadia]]<br />[[Raj Babbar]]<br />[[Raakhee]]<br />[[Amjad Khan (actor)|Amjad Khan]]\n| music          = [[Bhupen Hazarika]]\n| cinematography = [[Santosh Sivan]]<br /> Dharam Gulati\n| released       = {{Film date|1993|6|18|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 128 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = Hindi\n| budget         =\n}}\n'''''Rudaali''''' is a [[Bollywood films of 1993|1993]] Indian [[Hindi]]-language [[drama film]] directed by [[Kalpana Lajmi]], based on the short story written by famous [[Bengali people|Bengali]] author [[Mahasweta Devi]].<ref name=\"QuintLegacy\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thequint.com/india/2016/07/28/of-mourning-and-revolution-mahasweta-devis-legacy-on-the-screen-rudaali-hazaar-chaurasi-ki-maa|title=Mourning and Revolution: Mahasweta Devi's Legacy on the Screen|date=28 July 2016|website=The Quint|author=Maanvi|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/celebrities/story/mahasweta-devi-death-dead-famous-films-rudaali-hazaar-chaurasi-ki-maa-331939-2016-07-28|title=Mahasweta Devi, RIP: Rudaali to Sunghursh, 5 films that immortalise the author's works|first=Devarsi|last=Ghosh|date=28 July 2016|website=India Today|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> The film was selected as the Indian entry for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]] at the [[66th Academy Awards]], but was not accepted as a nominee.<ref>Margaret Herrick Library, Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences</ref><ref name=\"Variety\">{{cite journal | last = Frook | first = John Evan | title = Acad inks Cates, unveils foreign-language entries | journal = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=30 November 1993| url = http://www.variety.com/article/VR116185.html?categoryid=13&cs=1 | accessdate =25 August 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe film is set in a small village in [[Rajasthan]], [[India]]. It tells the story of a woman named Shanichari, who was abandoned by her mother shortly after her father's death. Bad fortune follows her throughout her life.\n\n==Cultural background==\nThe title is a reference to a custom in certain areas of Rajasthan where women of a lower caste are hired as [[professional mourners]] upon the death of upper-caste males. These women are referred to as a \"rudaali\" (roo-dah-lee), literally translated as \"female weeper\" or \"weeping woman\". Their job is to publicly express grief of family members who are not permitted to display emotion due to social status.<ref name=\"UIowa\">{{cite web| title = Rudaali| url = http://www.uiowa.edu/~incinema/Rudaali.html| work = University of Iowa| accessdate = 1 September 2014| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131019024024/http://www.uiowa.edu/~incinema/Rudaali.html| archivedate = 19 October 2013| df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nThe story begins with Ram Avtar, the zamindar ({{trans|landlord}}) of Barna (a village in the desert) realizing his imminent death, and the fact that none of his relatives would mourn him. He thus requests for the services of a famous rudaali named Bhikni ([[Rakhee Gulzar|Rakhee]]), to mourn for him once he dies. Bhikni ends up staying with the widow Shanichari, who lives within the Thakur's compound. As they both begin to bond, Shanichari tells Bhikni her life's story, which is revealed to us in flashbacks.\n\nShanichari was born on a ''Shanichar'' (Saturday), which is concerned to be an [[ill omen]]ed day, ruled by the planet ''Shani'' ([[Saturn]]) in astrology. Shanichari is blamed by the villagers for everything bad that happens around her - starting from her father's death, to her mother Peewli's running off to join a folk theatre troupe. While still young, Shanichari is married off to Ganju, a drunkard, who ends up dying due to a plague at a village fair. Her only support is her son, Budhua, whom she loves very much. However, he likes to roam around aimlessly, just like Peewli did.\n\nMeanwhile, the Thakur's son Lakshman Singh reveals that he likes her and offers her a job at the Thakur's ''[[haveli]]''. She then serves under his wife, who has been spoiled but is secluded from others. Lakshman tries to teach Shanichari to empower herself and understand her rights, and encourages her to \"look up\" into his eyes when speaking to him. One night, after Shanichari's singing performance at the ''haveli'', he gifts her a house of her own, along with two acres of land.\n\nSoon, the adult Budhua brings home a wife, Mungri, who is a young prostitute pregnant with his child. However, the couple keeps fighting, and one day in a fit of rage, Mungri [[Abortion|aborts]] the child. Budhua, upset, runs away from home, leaving his mother all alone. It is revealed that throughout her hardships, Shanichari had never shed a tear.\n\nOne night, Bhikni is called to the neighbouring village to meet Bhimdata. The Thakur passes away a few hours later. Lakshman Singh and Shanichari are then seen bidding farewell to each other as Singh plans to leave the village after his father's demise. They are interrupted by a messenger from Bhimdata, who reveals that Bhikni succumbed to the plague, and in her last few minutes requested that Shanichari be told that she was her mother, Peewli. Shanichari then begins to weep profusely, and takes over as the new rudaali, crying at the Thakur's funeral.<ref name=\"UIowa\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url= https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/1809394439/details# |title=Rudaali Production Details |website=Yahoo! Movies |access-date=15 January 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110522110439/http://movies.yahoo.com/movie/1809394439/details# |archive-date= 22 May 2011 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Dimple Kapadia]] as Shanichari\n* [[Amjad Khan (actor)|Amjad Khan]] as Ram Avtar, the zamindaar\n* [[Raj Babbar]] as Lakshman Singh, Ram Avtar's son\n* [[Rakhee Gulzar|Rakhee]] as Bhikni, a rudaali\n* [[Raghubir Yadav]] as an adult Budhua\n* [[Sushmita Mukherjee]] as Mungri, Budhua's wife\n* [[Mita Vashisht]]\n* [[Manohar Singh]]\n* Minaaz\n\n==Awards and honours==\n* Dimple Kapadia won the [[National Film Award for Best Actress]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/entertainment/dimple-kapadia-reacts-to-health-rumours-im-alive-and-kicking-2133795|title=Dimple Kapadia Reacts To Health Rumours: 'I'm Alive And Kicking'|website=NDTV.com|date=17 November 2019|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> and the [[Filmfare Awards]] Best Performance Critics Award.<ref name=\"ToIAwards\">{{Citation|title=Rudaali Awards: List of Awards won by Hindi movie Rudaali|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/movie-details/rudaali/movieawards/61335648.cms|work=Times of India|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Samir Chanda]] won the [[National Film Award for Best Art Direction]].<ref name=\"ToIAwards\" />\n* [[Simple Kapadia]] and Mala Dey won the [[National Film Award (India)|National Film Award]] for Best Costume Design.<ref name=\"ToIAwards\" />\n* Bhupen Hazarika was awarded the Best Music Director National Award in 1993.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/inspiring-lives/bhupen-hazarika-the-bard-of-brahmaputra/story-8IkggPd3dEu49dZN9D1sHJ.html|title=Bhupen Hazarika: The Bard of Brahmaputra|date=17 September 2019|website=Hindustan Times|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n* The film was India's official entry to the [[66th Academy Awards]] for the Best Foreign Language Film category.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/photogallery/movies/all-the-indian-films-that-were-indias-official-entry-to-the-academy-awards-2360805.html|title=Before Gully Boy, these Indian films were sent to the Academy Award for Best International Feature Film Category|date=10 February 2020|website=News18|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Amjad Khan (actor)|Amjad Khan]] died before the film was released, and the film is dedicated to him.<ref name=\"QuintLegacy\" />\n\n==Soundtrack==\nThe film has music by folk musician [[Bhupen Hazarika]].\n\n{{Track listing\n| all_music       = Bhupen Hazarika\n| all_lyrics      = [[Gulzar]]\n| extra_column    = Artist(s)\n| title1          = Dil Hoom Hoom Kare (Part-1)\n| extra1          = [[Lata Mangeshkar]]\n| note1            = Raga: [[Bhoopali]]\n| title2          = Dil Hoom Hoom Kare (Part-2)\n| extra2          = Bhupen Hazarika\n| note2            = Raga: Bhoopali\n| title3          = Jhuti Mooti Mitwa\n| extra3          = Lata Mangeshkar\n| note3            = Raga: [[Vrindavani sarang|Vrindavani Sarang]]\n| title4          = Samay O Dhire Chalo (Part-1)\n| extra4          = [[Asha Bhosle]]\n| note4            = Raga: [[Bhimpalasi]]\n| title5          = Samay O Dhire Chalo (Part-2)\n| extra5          = Bhupen Hazarika\n| note5            = Raga: Bhimpalasi\n| title6          = Moula O Moula\n| extra6          = Bhupen Hazarika\n| note6            = \n| title7          = Samay O Dhire Chalo (Part-3)\n| extra7          = Lata Mangeshkar\n| note7            = Raga: Bhimpalasi\n}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of submissions to the 66th Academy Awards for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n* [[List of Indian submissions for the Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0108001|title=Rudaali}}\n\n{{Indian submission for Academy Awards}}\n\n[[Category:1993 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:1990s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:1990s drama films]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Actress National Award-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films set in Rajasthan]]\n[[Category:Films based on short fiction]]\n[[Category:Films about women in India]]\n[[Category:Films about poverty in India]]\n[[Category:Death customs]]\n[[Category:Films whose production designer won the Best Production Design National Film Award]]\n[[Category:Films that won the Best Costume Design National Film Award]]\n", "name_user": "Fylindfotberserk", "label": "safe", "comment": "Generalformattingbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rudaali"}
{"title_page": "Sabian", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Sabaean}}\n{{About|the cymbal maker|the religion|Sabians|the professional wrestler|Sabian (wrestler)}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n|name             = Sabian\n|logo             = Sabian logo19.png\n|logo_size        = 250px\n|type             = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n|fate             = \n|foundation       = {{Start date and age|1981}} in [[Meductic, New Brunswick|Meductic]], [[Canada]]\n|founder          = [[Robert Zildjian]] \n|location_city    = [[Meductic, New Brunswick]]\n|location_country = [[Canada]]\n|key_people       = Andy Zildjian (president/CEO)<br/>Sally Zildjian-Teague\n|revenue          = \n|owner            = \n|industry         = [[Musical instrument]]s\n|num_employees    = \n|products         = [[Cymbal]]s\n|brands           = [[Crescent cymbals|Crescent]] <ref name=cres>[https://www.moderndrummer.com/2015/02/news-crescent-cymbals-acquired-sabian/ Crescent cymbals acquired by Sabian] on Modern Drummer, Feb 2015</ref>\n|subsid           = \n|parent           = \n|homepage         = [http://www.sabian.com/ sabian.com]\n}}\n\n'''Sabian''' is a [[Canada|Canadian]] [[cymbal]] [[manufacturing company]] established in 1981 in [[Meductic, New Brunswick]], where it is still headquartered. Sabian is considered one of the ''big four'' manufacturers of cymbals, along with [[Avedis Zildjian Company|Zildjian]], [[Meinl Percussion|Meinl]] and [[Paiste]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Crash Clash: The Shared History of Zildjian and Sabian Cymbals |url=https://reverb.com/news/crash-clash-the-shared-history-of-zidjian-and-sabian |website=Reverb |publisher=Reverb |accessdate=11 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nSabian Cymbals was founded in 1981, by Robert Zildjian, when he had a conflict with his brother Armand after he was not chosen to be the main CEO and successor of Avedis Zildjian. Robert opened Sabian in the small eastern Canadian village of [[Meductic, New Brunswick]]. The name 'Sabian' comes from the first two letters of the names of Robert's three children (Sally, Billy, and Andy).<ref>{{cite web |title=Robert Zildjian, world-famous cymbal pioneer, dies in Brunswick |url=http://bangordailynews.com/2013/04/01/news/midcoast/robert-zildjian-world-famous-cymbal-pioneer-dies-in-brunswick/ |website=Bangor Daily News |publisher=Bangor Daily News |accessdate=11 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Crash 41808 18\" B8 firmy Sabian.jpg|thumb|left|150px|18\" crash cymbal by Sabian]]\nIn 1982, Sabian introduced the Automatic Anvil (AA) and the Hand Hammered (HH) lines, producing 45,000 cymbals in the first year.<ref name=\"revbian\">{{cite web |title=The Sabian story a timeline of cymbal craft |url=https://reverb.com/news/the-sabian-story-a-timeline-of-cymbal-craft |website=Reverb |publisher=Reverb |accessdate=11 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1989, Sabian produced its first signature artist cymbals, the [[Jack DeJohnette]] [[ride cymbal|ride]]/[[hi-hat]]s, and the [[Carmine Appice]] Silver Nickel [[China cymbal|Chinese]].<ref name=\"revbian\"/> Eight years later, due to rising demand, a larger plant was opened in Meductic.<ref name=\"revbian\"/>\n\nSabian introduced the HHX series in 2001 which brought in the Manhattan's darker hammering techniques.<ref name=\"revbian\"/> In 2011, with the help of Jojo Mayer, Sabian produced the OMNI series, which was the product of years of research and development.<ref name=\"revbian\"/>\n\nSabian cymbals are still made in New Brunswick.<ref name=\"cbc.ca\">{{cite web |title=Robert Zildjian, Sabian Cymbals founder, dies at 89 |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/robert-zildjian-sabian-cymbals-founder-dies-at-89-1.1366113 |website=CBC |publisher=CBC |accessdate=11 August 2018}}</ref> Robert's son Andy is the most recent president of Sabian.<ref name=\"cbc.ca\"/> In January 2015, the company announced the acquisition of [[United States|US]] cymbal manufacturer, [[Crescent cymbals]], moving all its production to Sabian's factory in Canada, subsequently incorporating Crescent as its list of brands.<ref name=cres/>\n\nIn 2017, Sabian sponsored \"The Capital Project Presents: The Final Concert\", a music and film event in [[Fredericton]], New Brunswick, making the event free of charge. Refunds were offered to people who had already purchased tickets.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sabian Cymbals Buys Tickets so People Can Attend 'Capital Project' Event for Free |url=http://huddle.today/sabian-cymbals-sponsors-new-brunswick-film-and-concert-event/ |website=Huddle Today |publisher=Huddle Today |accessdate=11 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Sabian}}\n* [https://sabian.com/ Official website]\n* [https://www.namm.org/library/oral-history/robert-zildjian Robert Zildjian Interview] NAMM Oral History Library (2002)\n* [https://www.namm.org/library/oral-history/willi-zildjian Willi Zildjian Interview] NAMM Oral History Library (2002)\n* [https://www.namm.org/library/oral-history/andy-zildjian Andy Zildjian Interview] NAMM Oral History Library (2012)\n\n{{Percussion instruments brands}}\n{{Coord|45|59|38.76|N|67|28|42.96|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Percussion instrument manufacturing companies]]\n[[Category:Cymbal manufacturing companies]]\n[[Category:Companies based in New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies established in 1981]]\n[[Category:1981 establishments in New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Canadian brands]]\n[[Category:York County, New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Musical instrument manufacturing companies of Canada]]\n\n\n{{Percussion-instrument-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Sabaean}}\n{{About|the cymbal maker|the religion|Sabians|the professional wrestler|Sabian (wrestler)}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n|name             = Sabian\n|logo             = Sabian logo19.png\n|logo_size        = 250px\n|type             = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n|fate             = \n|foundation       = {{Start date and age|1981}} in [[Meductic, New Brunswick|Meductic]], [[Canada]]\n|founder          = [[Robert Zildjian]] \n|location_city    = [[Meductic, New Brunswick]]\n|location_country = [[Canada]]\n|key_people       = Andy Zildjian (president/CEO)<br/>Sally Zildjian-Teague\n|revenue          = \n|owner            = \n|industry         = [[Musical instrument]]s\n|num_employees    = \n|products         = [[Cymbal]]s\n|brands           = [[Crescent cymbals|Crescent]] <ref name=cres>[https://www.moderndrummer.com/2015/02/news-crescent-cymbals-acquired-sabian/ Crescent cymbals acquired by Sabian] on Modern Drummer, Feb 2015</ref>\n|subsid           = \n|parent           = \n|homepage         = [http://www.sabian.com/ sabian.com]\n}}\n\n'''Sabana''' is a [[Canada|Canadian]] [[cymbal]] [[manufacturing company]] established in 1981 in [[Meductic, New Brunswick]], where it is still headquartered. Sabian is considered one of the ''big four'' manufacturers of cymbals, along with [[Avedis Zildjian Company|Zildjian]], [[Meinl Percussion|Meinl]] and [[Paiste]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Crash Clash: The Shared History of Zildjian and Sabian Cymbals |url=https://reverb.com/news/crash-clash-the-shared-history-of-zidjian-and-sabian |website=Reverb |publisher=Reverb |accessdate=11 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nSabian Cymbals was founded in 1981, by Robert Zildjian, when he had a conflict with his brother Armand after he was not chosen to be the main CEO and successor of Avedis Zildjian. Robert opened Sabian in the small eastern Canadian village of [[Meductic, New Brunswick]]. The name 'Sabian' comes from the first two letters of the names of Robert's three children (Sally, Billy, and Andy).<ref>{{cite web |title=Robert Zildjian, world-famous cymbal pioneer, dies in Brunswick |url=http://bangordailynews.com/2013/04/01/news/midcoast/robert-zildjian-world-famous-cymbal-pioneer-dies-in-brunswick/ |website=Bangor Daily News |publisher=Bangor Daily News |accessdate=11 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Crash 41808 18\" B8 firmy Sabian.jpg|thumb|left|150px|18\" crash cymbal by Sabian]]\nIn 1982, Sabian introduced the Automatic Anvil (AA) and the Hand Hammered (HH) lines, producing 45,000 cymbals in the first year.<ref name=\"revbian\">{{cite web |title=The Sabian story a timeline of cymbal craft |url=https://reverb.com/news/the-sabian-story-a-timeline-of-cymbal-craft |website=Reverb |publisher=Reverb |accessdate=11 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1989, Sabian produced its first signature artist cymbals, the [[Jack DeJohnette]] [[ride cymbal|ride]]/[[hi-hat]]s, and the [[Carmine Appice]] Silver Nickel [[China cymbal|Chinese]].<ref name=\"revbian\"/> Eight years later, due to rising demand, a larger plant was opened in Meductic.<ref name=\"revbian\"/>\n\nSabian introduced the HHX series in 2001 which brought in the Manhattan's darker hammering techniques.<ref name=\"revbian\"/> In 2011, with the help of Jojo Mayer, Sabian produced the OMNI series, which was the product of years of research and development.<ref name=\"revbian\"/>\n\nSabian cymbals are still made in New Brunswick.<ref name=\"cbc.ca\">{{cite web |title=Robert Zildjian, Sabian Cymbals founder, dies at 89 |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/robert-zildjian-sabian-cymbals-founder-dies-at-89-1.1366113 |website=CBC |publisher=CBC |accessdate=11 August 2018}}</ref> Robert's son Andy is the most recent president of Sabian.<ref name=\"cbc.ca\"/> In January 2015, the company announced the acquisition of [[United States|US]] cymbal manufacturer, [[Crescent cymbals]], moving all its production to Sabian's factory in Canada, subsequently incorporating Crescent as its list of brands.<ref name=cres/>\n\nIn 2017, Sabian sponsored \"The Capital Project Presents: The Final Concert\", a music and film event in [[Fredericton]], New Brunswick, making the event free of charge. Refunds were offered to people who had already purchased tickets.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sabian Cymbals Buys Tickets so People Can Attend 'Capital Project' Event for Free |url=http://huddle.today/sabian-cymbals-sponsors-new-brunswick-film-and-concert-event/ |website=Huddle Today |publisher=Huddle Today |accessdate=11 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Sabian}}\n* [https://sabian.com/ Official website]\n* [https://www.namm.org/library/oral-history/robert-zildjian Robert Zildjian Interview] NAMM Oral History Library (2002)\n* [https://www.namm.org/library/oral-history/willi-zildjian Willi Zildjian Interview] NAMM Oral History Library (2002)\n* [https://www.namm.org/library/oral-history/andy-zildjian Andy Zildjian Interview] NAMM Oral History Library (2012)\n\n{{Percussion instruments brands}}\n{{Coord|45|59|38.76|N|67|28|42.96|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Percussion instrument manufacturing companies]]\n[[Category:Cymbal manufacturing companies]]\n[[Category:Companies based in New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies established in 1981]]\n[[Category:1981 establishments in New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Canadian brands]]\n[[Category:York County, New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Musical instrument manufacturing companies of Canada]]\n\n\n{{Percussion-instrument-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jrinnyc", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sabian"}
{"title_page": "Lanchester King", "text_new": "'''George Lanchester King'''<ref>{{Cite journal|title=University Intelligence. Cambridge, Jan. 17|journal=The Times|date=18 January 1889|page= 10 col F|issue=32599}}</ref> was the second Anglican [[Bishop of Madagascar]]<ref>[https://openlibrary.org/b/OL17951549M/Christian-missions-in-Madagascar Open Library]</ref> from 1899 to 1919.<ref>[[Who's Who|\u201cWho was Who\u201d]]1897-1990 London, [[A & C Black]], 1991 {{ISBN|0-7136-3457-X}}</ref>\n\nHe was born in 1860 and educated at [[Clare College, Cambridge]].<ref>{{acad|id=KN879GL|name=King, George Lanchester}}</ref> Ordained in 1884,<ref>\"The Clergy List, Clerical Guide and Ecclesiastical Directory\" London, Hamilton & Co 1889</ref> he began his career with [[Curate|curacies]] at St&nbsp;Andrew, [[Tudhoe Grange]] and Holy Trinity, [[Gateshead]]. He was made deacon on [[Trinity Sunday]] 1884 (8&nbsp;June) at [[Bishop Auckland#St Andrew's Church|St&nbsp;Andrew's Church, Bishop Auckland]]<ref>{{Church Times | title = Ordinations on Sunday last | archive = 1884_06_13_446 | issue = 1116 | date = 13 June 1884 | page = 446 | accessed = 30 October 2019 }}</ref> and ordained priest the following Trinity Sunday (31&nbsp;May 1885) at [[Durham Cathedral]] \u2014 both times by [[J.&nbsp;B. Lightfoot]], [[Bishop of Durham]].<ref>{{Church Times | title = Ordinations on Sunday last | archive = 1885_06_05_438 | issue = 1167 | date = 5 June 1885 | page = 438 | accessed = 30 October 2019 }}</ref> He was then [[Vicar]] of St&nbsp;Mary, [[South Shields]] until 1899 when he was appointed to the [[Colony|colonial]] [[episcopate]]<ref>{{Cite journal|journal=The Times]]|date=30 June 1899|page=8 col E|issue=35869|title=Ecclesiastical Intelligence Consecration of Three Bishops}}</ref> \u2014 he was consecrated a bishop on St&nbsp;Peter's Day (29&nbsp;June) 1899 by [[Frederick Temple]], [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], at [[St&nbsp;Paul's Cathedral]].<ref>{{Church Times | title = Consecration of bishops | archive = 1899_06_30_783 | issue = 1901 | date = 30 June 1899 | page = 783 | accessed = 30 October 2019 }}</ref> On his return to [[England]]<ref>[http://archives.lambethpalacelibrary.org.uk/CalmView/Record.aspx?src=CalmView.Catalog&id=LC%2f1920%2f134%2f404-23%2c+427-33 National Church Institutions Database of Manuscripts and Archives]</ref> he was [[Secretary]] of the [[USPG|Society for Propagation of the Gospel]]; then a [[Canon Residentiary]] of [[Rochester Cathedral]] (1923\u20131940) and an [[Assistant Bishop of Rochester]] (1928\u20131939). He died in Woking on 26 January 1941.<ref> '' Obituary Dr G.L. King'' [[The Times]] Wednesday, 19 February 1941; pg. 7; Issue 48854; col E</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [[:fr:Cath\u00e9drale_Saint_Laurent_Ambohimanoro|Cath\u00e9drale Saint Laurent Ambohimanoro]]\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-rel|}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Kestell Kestell-Cornish]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Bishop of Madagascar]]|years=1899 &ndash; 1919}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[George Kestell-Cornish]]}}\n{{end}}\n{{Bishops of Madagascar}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2016}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:King, Lanchester}}\n[[Category:1860 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Clare College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:19th-century Anglican bishops]]\n[[Category:20th-century Anglican bishops]]\n[[Category:Bishops of Madagascar]]\n[[Category:1941 deaths]]\n{{Anglican-bishop-stub}}\n{{Madagascar-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''George Lanchester King'''<ref>{{Cite journal|title=University Intelligence. Cambridge, Jan. 17|journal=The Times|date=18 January 1889|page= 10 col F|issue=32599}}</ref> was the second Anglican [[Bishop of Madagascar]]<ref>[https://openlibrary.org/b/OL17951549M/Christian-missions-in-Madagascar Open Library]</ref> from 1899 to 1919.<ref>[[Who's Who|\u201cWho was Who\u201d]]1897-1990 London, [[A & C Black]], 1991 {{ISBN|0-7136-3457-X}}</ref>\n\nHe was born in 1860 and educated at [[Clare College, Cambridge]].<ref>{{acad|id=KN879GL|name=King, George Lanchester}}</ref> Ordained in 1884,<ref>\"The Clergy List, Clerical Guide and Ecclesiastical Directory\" London, Hamilton & Co 1889</ref> he began his career with [[Curate|curacies]] at St&nbsp;Andrew, [[Tudhoe Grange]] and Holy Trinity, [[Gateshead]]. He was made deacon on [[Trinity Sunday]] 1884 (8&nbsp;June) at [[Bishop Auckland#St Andrew's Church|St&nbsp;Andrew's Church, Bishop Auckland]]<ref>{{Church Times | title = Ordinations on Sunday last | archive = 1884_06_13_446 | issue = 1116 | date = 13 June 1884 | page = 446 | accessed = 30 October 2019 }}</ref> and ordained priest the following Trinity Sunday (31&nbsp;May 1885) at [[Durham Cathedral]] \u2014 both times by [[J.&nbsp;B. Lightfoot]], [[Bishop of Durham]].<ref>{{Church Times | title = Ordinations on Sunday last | archive = 1885_06_05_438 | issue = 1167 | date = 5 June 1885 | page = 438 | accessed = 30 October 2019 }}</ref> He was then [[Vicar]] of St&nbsp;Mary, [[South Shields]] until 1899 when he was appointed to the [[Colony|colonial]] [[episcopate]]<ref>{{Cite journal|journal=The Times]]|date=30 June 1899|page=8 col E|issue=35869|title=Ecclesiastical Intelligence Consecration of Three Bishops}}</ref> \u2014 he was consecrated a bishop on St&nbsp;Peter's Day (29&nbsp;June) 1899 by [[Frederick Temple]], [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], at [[St&nbsp;Paul's Cathedral]].<ref>{{Church Times | title = Consecration of bishops | archive = 1899_06_30_783 | issue = 1901 | date = 30 June 1899 | page = 783 | accessed = 30 October 2019 }}</ref> On his return to [[England]]<ref>[http://archives.lambethpalacelibrary.org.uk/CalmView/Record.aspx?src=CalmView.Catalog&id=LC%2f1920%2f134%2f404-23%2c+427-33 National Church Institutions Database of Manuscripts and Archives]</ref> he was [[Secretary]] of the [[USPG|Society for Propagation of the Gospel]]; then a [[Canon Residentiary]] of [[Rochester Cathedral]] (1923\u20131940) and an [[Assistant Bishop of Rochester]] (1928\u20131939). He died in Woking on 26 January 1941.<ref> '' Obituary Dr G.L. King'' [[The Times]] Wednesday, 19 February 1941; pg. 7; Issue 48854; col E</ref>\n\n==Refernces==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [[:fr:Cath\u00e9drale_Saint_Laurent_Ambohimanoro|Cath\u00e9drale Saint Laurent Ambohimanoro]]\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-rel|}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Kestell Kestell-Cornish]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Bishop of Madagascar]]|years=1899 &ndash; 1919}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[George Kestell-Cornish]]}}\n{{end}}\n{{Bishops of Madagascar}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2016}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:King, Lanchester}}\n[[Category:1860 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Clare College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:19th-century Anglican bishops]]\n[[Category:20th-century Anglican bishops]]\n[[Category:Bishops of Madagascar]]\n[[Category:1941 deaths]]\n{{Anglican-bishop-stub}}\n{{Madagascar-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Damien Linnane", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRefernces:typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lanchester_King"}
{"title_page": "Mount Makaturing", "text_new": "{{Infobox mountain\n| name              = Makaturing\n| other_name        = \n| photo             = \n| photo_size        = \n| photo_alt         = \n| photo_caption     = \n| elevation         = \n| elevation_m       = 1908\n| elevation_ft      = <ref name=\"PHIVOLCS-Makaturing\">{{cite web |title=Makaturing |url=http://volcano.phivolcs.dost.gov.ph/update_VMEPD/Volcano/VolcanoList/makaturing.htm |website=Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology |accessdate=19 March 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100117082256/http://volcano.phivolcs.dost.gov.ph/update_VMEPD/Volcano/VolcanoList/makaturing.htm |archivedate=17 Jan 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"GVP-Makaturing\">{{cite gvp|vn=271040|name=Makaturing}}</ref>\n| elevation_ref     = \n| prominence        = \n| prominence_m      = \n| prominence_ft     = \n| prominence_ref    = \n| listing           = [[List of active volcanoes in the Philippines|Active volcano]]\n| range             = \n| parent_peak       = \n| location          = <!-- [[Mindanao]] -->\n| country           = [[Philippines]]\n| state             = [[Bangsamoro Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao|BARMM]]\n| state_type        = [[Regions of the Philippines|Region]]\n| region            = [[Lanao del Sur]]\n| region_type       = [[Provinces of the Philippines|Province]]\n| city              = [[Butig]]\n| city_type         = [[Cities of the Philippines|City]]/[[Municipalities of the Philippines|municipality]]\n| map               = Mindanao#Philippines\n| map_alt           = \n| map_caption       = <!-- Location within the Philippines -->\n| map_size          = \n| label             = \n| label_position    = \n| coordinates       = {{coord|7|39|N|124|19|E|type:mountain_region:PH_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| range_coordinates = \n| coordinates_ref   = \n| topo              = \n| type              = [[Stratovolcano]]<ref name=\"PHIVOLCS-Makaturing\" /><ref name=\"GVP-Makaturing\" />\n| volcanic_arc/belt = [[Central Mindanao Arc]]<ref name=\"PHIVOLCS-Makaturing\" />\n| age               = \n| last_eruption     = {{date|18 Mar 1882}}<ref name=\"PHIVOLCS-Makaturing\" /><ref name=\"GVP-Makaturing\" />\n| first_ascent      = \n| easiest_route     = \n| embedded          = {{Infobox mapframe|id={{#invoke:Wikibase|id}}|coord={{#invoke:coordinates|coord}}|wikidata=yes}} \n}}\n\n'''Makaturing''', is a [[stratovolcano]] on [[Mindanao]] island in the [[Philippines]]. It is found in the province of [[Lanao del Sur]] (particularly in the town of [[Butig]]) in the [[Bangsamoro Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao]]. Makaturing has an elevation of {{Convert|1940|m|ft|0}} and a base diameter of {{Convert|29|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}. It is part of a string of volcanoes called the [[Central Mindanao Arc]].<ref name=\"PHIVOLCS-Makaturing\" />\n\ne Smithsonian Institution's Global Volcanology Program, citing the ''Catalog of Active Volcanoes of the World'' (Neumann van Padang, 1953), suggests that some eruptions were actually those of neighboring [[Ragang]] volcano.<ref name=\"GVP-Makaturing\" />\n\nMakaturing is one of the [[List of active volcanoes in the Philippines|active volcanoes in the Philippines]]. All are part of the [[Pacific Ring of Fire]].<ref name=\"PHIVOLCS-Inactive\">{{cite web |title=Inactive Volcanoes Part 5 |url=http://www.phivolcs.dost.gov.ph/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=424:inactive-volcanoes&catid=55:volcanoes-of-the-philippines |website=Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology |accessdate=19 March 2019 |archiveurl=http://www.phivolcs.dost.gov.ph/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=424:inactive-volcanoes&catid=55:volcanoes-of-the-philippines |archivedate=11 Mar 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Historical events==\nOn May 18, 1947, [[Philippine Air Force]] (PAF) commander Gen. Edwin Andrews died with 16 others when the C-47 transport plane carrying them crashed in Makaturing. Nine years later, the PAF established an air base in [[Zamboanga City]] and is now named the [[Edwin Andrews Air Base]] from where the Philippine military launches air support operations in the ongoing campaign against separatists.<ref name=\"PAFMilPH\">{{cite web |title=Edwin Andrews Air Base |url=https://www.paf.mil.ph/bases/edwin-andrews-air-base |website=Philippine Air Force |accessdate=19 March 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190319053651/https://www.paf.mil.ph/bases/edwin-andrews-air-base |archivedate=19 March 2019}}</ref>\n==May 18,1947 (Sunday)==\n*A young man Tawalangen 19 years from Masiu, growing up to Macadar he said, i witness the Plane crash in \"Palaw a Magaturing\" that mean mount Makaturing on the spot fallin down on Sunday morning.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of active volcanoes in the Philippines]]\n* [[List of inactive volcanoes in the Philippines]]\n* [[List of potentially active volcanoes in the Philippines]]\n* [[Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100117082256/http://volcano.phivolcs.dost.gov.ph/update_VMEPD/Volcano/VolcanoList/makaturing.htm Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology (PHIVOLCS) Makaturing Volcano Page (archived)]\n* {{cite gvp|vn=271040|name=Makaturing}}\n\n{{Volcanoes of the Philippines}}\n\n[[Category:Stratovolcanoes of the Philippines|Makaturing]]\n[[Category:Subduction volcanoes|Makaturing]]\n[[Category:Volcanoes of Mindanao|Makaturing]]\n[[Category:Mountains of the Philippines|Makaturing]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Lanao del Sur]]\n[[Category:Active volcanoes of the Philippines|Makaturing]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox mountain\n| name              = Makaturing\n| other_name        = \n| photo             = \n| photo_size        = \n| photo_alt         = \n| photo_caption     = \n| elevation         = \n| elevation_m       = 1908\n| elevation_ft      = <ref name=\"PHIVOLCS-Makaturing\">{{cite web |title=Makaturing |url=http://volcano.phivolcs.dost.gov.ph/update_VMEPD/Volcano/VolcanoList/makaturing.htm |website=Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology |accessdate=19 March 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100117082256/http://volcano.phivolcs.dost.gov.ph/update_VMEPD/Volcano/VolcanoList/makaturing.htm |archivedate=17 Jan 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"GVP-Makaturing\">{{cite gvp|vn=271040|name=Makaturing}}</ref>\n| elevation_ref     = \n| prominence        = \n| prominence_m      = \n| prominence_ft     = \n| prominence_ref    = \n| listing           = [[List of active volcanoes in the Philippines|Active volcano]]\n| range             = \n| parent_peak       = \n| location          = <!-- [[Mindanao]] -->\n| country           = [[Philippines]]\n| state             = [[Bangsamoro Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao|BARMM]]\n| state_type        = [[Regions of the Philippines|Region]]\n| region            = [[Lanao del Sur]]\n| region_type       = [[Provinces of the Philippines|Province]]\n| city              = [[Butig]]\n| city_type         = [[Cities of the Philippines|City]]/[[Municipalities of the Philippines|municipality]]\n| map               = Mindanao#Philippines\n| map_alt           = \n| map_caption       = <!-- Location within the Philippines -->\n| map_size          = \n| label             = \n| label_position    = \n| coordinates       = {{coord|7|39|N|124|19|E|type:mountain_region:PH_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| range_coordinates = \n| coordinates_ref   = \n| topo              = \n| type              = [[Stratovolcano]]<ref name=\"PHIVOLCS-Makaturing\" /><ref name=\"GVP-Makaturing\" />\n| volcanic_arc/belt = [[Central Mindanao Arc]]<ref name=\"PHIVOLCS-Makaturing\" />\n| age               = \n| last_eruption     = {{date|18 Mar 1882}}<ref name=\"PHIVOLCS-Makaturing\" /><ref name=\"GVP-Makaturing\" />\n| first_ascent      = \n| easiest_route     = \n| embedded          = {{Infobox mapframe|id={{#invoke:Wikibase|id}}|coord={{#invoke:coordinates|coord}}|wikidata=yes}} \n}}\n\n'''Makaturing''', is a [[stratovolcano]] on [[Mindanao]] island in the [[Philippines]]. It is found in the province of [[Lanao del Sur]] (particularly in the town of [[Butig]]) in the [[Bangsamoro Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao]]. Makaturing has an elevation of {{Convert|1940|m|ft|0}} and a base diameter of {{Convert|29|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}. It is part of a string of volcanoes called the [[Central Mindanao Arc]].<ref name=\"PHIVOLCS-Makaturing\" />\n\ne Smithsonian Institution's Global Volcanology Program, citing the ''Catalog of Active Volcanoes of the World'' (Neumann van Padang, 1953), suggests that some eruptions were actually those of neighboring [[Ragang]] volcano.<ref name=\"GVP-Makaturing\" />\n\nMakaturing is one of the [[List of active volcanoes in the Philippines|active volcanoes in the Philippines]]. All are part of the [[Pacific Ring of Fire]].<ref name=\"PHIVOLCS-Inactive\">{{cite web |title=Inactive Volcanoes Part 5 |url=http://www.phivolcs.dost.gov.ph/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=424:inactive-volcanoes&catid=55:volcanoes-of-the-philippines |website=Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology |accessdate=19 March 2019 |archiveurl=http://www.phivolcs.dost.gov.ph/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=424:inactive-volcanoes&catid=55:volcanoes-of-the-philippines |archivedate=11 Mar 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Historical events==\nOn May 18, 1947, [[Philippine Air Force]] (PAF) commander Gen. Edwin Andrews died with 16 others when the C-47 transport plane carrying them crashed in Makaturing. Nine years later, the PAF established an air base in [[Zamboanga City]] and is now named the [[Edwin Andrews Air Base]] from where the Philippine military launches air support operations in the ongoing campaign against separatists.<ref name=\"PAFMilPH\">{{cite web |title=Edwin Andrews Air Base |url=https://www.paf.mil.ph/bases/edwin-andrews-air-base |website=Philippine Air Force |accessdate=19 March 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190319053651/https://www.paf.mil.ph/bases/edwin-andrews-air-base |archivedate=19 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of active volcanoes in the Philippines]]\n* [[List of inactive volcanoes in the Philippines]]\n* [[List of potentially active volcanoes in the Philippines]]\n* [[Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100117082256/http://volcano.phivolcs.dost.gov.ph/update_VMEPD/Volcano/VolcanoList/makaturing.htm Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology (PHIVOLCS) Makaturing Volcano Page (archived)]\n* {{cite gvp|vn=271040|name=Makaturing}}\n\n{{Volcanoes of the Philippines}}\n\n[[Category:Stratovolcanoes of the Philippines|Makaturing]]\n[[Category:Subduction volcanoes|Makaturing]]\n[[Category:Volcanoes of Mindanao|Makaturing]]\n[[Category:Mountains of the Philippines|Makaturing]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Lanao del Sur]]\n[[Category:Active volcanoes of the Philippines|Makaturing]]\n", "name_user": "119.94.97.12", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHistorical events)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mount_Makaturing"}
