0438\u043d\u0430\u043b\u0430\u043d \u0442\u0440\u0438\u043b\u0435\u0440 |work=[[Radio Television of Serbia|RTS]] |date=19 Nov 2017 |accessdate=2020-01-21 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://rs.n1info.com/Showbiz/a432162/Za-nedelju-dana-film-Juzni-vetar-pogledalo-100.000-ljudi.html |title=Za nedelju dana film Ju\u017eni vetar pogledalo 100.000 ljudi |work=[[N1 (TV channel)|N1]] |date=31 October 2018 |accessdate=2020-01-21 }}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Milo\u0161 Bikovi\u0107]] - Petar Mara\u0161\n*[[Neboj\u0161a Glogovac]] - Golub\n*[[Dragan Bjelogrli\u0107]] - Dragoslav \u201eCar\u201d\n*{{ill|Miodrag Radonji\u0107|sr}} - Ba\u0107a\n\n==Soundtrack==\n===Track listing===\n{{tracklist\n|total_length =21:21\n|title1  =4 strane sveta\n|length1 =2:44\n|title2  =Grmi\n|length2 =2:50\n|title3  =Ma\u010de\n|length3 =3:32\n|title4  =Ju\u017eni vetar gas\n|length4 =3:17\n|title5  =Grad greha\n|length5 =3:26\n|title6 =Mojne s' nama\n|length6 =3:18\n|title7  =Hollywood\n|length7 =2:14\n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|5207158}}\n\n[[Category:Serbian crime films]]\n[[Category:2010s crime action films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Belgrade]]\n\n{{Serbia-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "SrpskiAnonimac", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_Wind_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Russula heterophylla", "text_new": "{{Taxobox\n| image = Russ.het.jpg\n| image_width=235px\n| regnum = [[Fungus|Fungi]]\n| divisio = [[Basidiomycota]]\n| classis = [[Agaricomycetes]]\n| ordo = [[Russulales]]\n| familia = [[Russulaceae]]\n| genus = '''''[[Russula]]'''''\n| species = '''''R. heterophylla'''''\n| binomial = ''Russula heterophylla''\n| binomial_authority = [[Elias Magnus Fries|(Fr.) Fri.]]\n}}\n{{mycomorphbox \n| name = ''Russula heterophylla''\n| whichGills =  adnexed\n| capShape = convex\n|capShape2=flat\n| hymeniumType=gills\n| stipeCharacter= bare\n| sporePrintColor=white\n| howEdible=edible\n}}\nThe [[edible mushroom|edible]] wild mushroom '''''Russula heterophylla''''', that has lately been given the [[common name]] of the '''greasy green brittlegill'''<ref name=Phillips06>{{cite book | author = Roger Phillips | year = 2006  | title = Mushrooms | publisher = Pan MacMillan | isbn = 978-0-330-44237-4}}</ref> is placed in the genus ''[[Russula]]'', the members of which are mostly known as '''brittlegills'''.  It is a variably colored mushroom, found in [[deciduous]] forests, and woods in [[Great Britain|Britain]], [[Europe]], and [[Scandinavia]].<ref name=C&D1995>{{cite book | author = Regis Courtecuisse and Bernard Duhem  | year = 1995 | title = Mushrooms and Toadstools of Britain and Europe | publisher = Harper Collins | isbn = 978-0-00-220025-7}}</ref> Appearing with broad-leaved trees in summer to early autumn, it usually has a greenish coloration.\n\n==Taxonomy==\nNoted and described by the [[South Africa]]n-born [[mycologist]] [[Christian Hendrik Persoon]] as ''Agaricus lividus'' in 1801. It was placed in the ''[[Russula]]'' [[Genus]] by the Swedish mycologist, and botanist [[Elias Magnus Fries]] in 1838, with the epithet ''heterophylla''. Despite many changes, by several mycologists over the years since then, it is this binomial that is currently recognised,<ref>http://www.indexfungorum.org/Names/SynSpecies.asp?RecordID=193557</ref> and is in use at present.\n\nThe variants ''Russula heterophylla'' var. ''chlora'' Gillet 1876, and ''Russula heterophylla'' var. ''virginea'' (Cooke and Massee) A.Pearson & Dennis, have been given species status as ''[[Russula violeipes]]'', and ''[[Russula virginea]]'' respectively.\n\n==Description==\nThe [[pileus (mycology)|cap]] is {{convert|5|to|10|cm|in}} in diameter. It is known to vary in colour, and can be various shades of green, brown, or ochre. It is initially round, flattening with age, and laters develops a depression. The white [[stipe (mycology)|stem]] is firm, browning, and gives a salmon reaction when rubbed with [[ferrous sulphate]]. The [[Lamella (mycology)|gills]] are adnexed, and white giving a [[spore print]] of the same colour.<ref name=Phillips06/>\n\n===Microscopic characteristics===\nThe [[basidiospore|spores]] are the smallest in the genus, and are 5\u20137 by 4\u20136&nbsp;[[micrometre|\u00b5m]],  spherical to elliptical, or pear shaped; warts 0.2\u20130.6&nbsp;\u00b5m high, mostly isolated, but occasionally two or three joined together, or connected by a line.<ref name=Phillips06/>\n\n===Similar species===\nGreen forms of ''Russula cyanoxantha'' can be distinguished, because they give a greenish reaction, or no reaction when rubbed with [[ferrous sulphate]] (iron salts), and have the flexible, 'greasy' feeling gills characteristic of that species.\n\n''[[Russula virescens]]'' (Schaeff.) Fr.,  has a cracked or fragmented cap surface.\n\n''[[Russula aeruginea]]'' Fr.,  grows with [[Birch]].\n\n''[[Russula langei]]'' Bon, also has a green reaction to ferrous sulphate, and smells like shellfish, with flesh that stains orange-brown.\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\n''Russula heterophylla'' appears in summer to early autumn, usually growing in small groups. It is occasional in [[Great Britain|Britain]], [[Europe]], and [[Scandinavia]].<ref name=C&D1995/> It grows with several species of [[deciduous|broad-leaved]] trees, on the roots of which it is [[ectomycorrhizal]].\n\n==Edibility==\nThis mushroom is [[edible mushroom|edible]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Phillips |first=Roger |title=Mushrooms and Other Fungi of North America |year=2010 |origyear=2005 |publisher=Firefly Books |location=Buffalo, NY |isbn=978-1-55407-651-2 |p=141}}</ref> and good, although care must be taken as it is very like the deadly ''[[Amanita phalloides]]'' (death cap) when young. It is also prone to slug attacks.\n\n==See also==\n[[List of Russula species|List of ''Russula'' species]]\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.pbase.com/tmurray74/image/31682622 ''Russula heterophylla'']\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1415480}}\n\n[[Category:Fungi of Europe]]\n[[Category:Edible fungi]]\n[[Category:Russula|heterophylla]]\n\n\n{{Russulales-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Taxobox\n| image = Russ.het.jpg\n| image_width=235px\n| regnum = [[Fungus|Fungi]]\n| divisio = [[Basidiomycota]]\n| classis = [[Agaricomycetes]]\n| ordo = [[Russulales]]\n| familia = [[Russulaceae]]\n| genus = '''''[[Russula]]'''''\n| species = '''''R. heterophylla'''''\n| binomial = ''Russula heterophylla''\n| binomial_authority = [[Elias Magnus Fries|(Fr.) Fri.]]\n}}\n{{mycomorphbox \n| name = ''Russula heterophylla''\n| whichGills =  adnexed\n| capShape = convex\n|capShape2=flat\n| hymeniumType=gills\n| stipeCharacter= bare\n| sporePrintColor=white\n| howEdible=edible\n}}\nThe [[edible mushroom|edible]] wild mushroom '''''Russula heterophylla''''', that has lately been given the [[common name]] of the '''greasy green brittlegill'''<ref name=Phillips06>{{cite book | author = Roger Phillips | year = 2006  | title = Mushrooms | publisher = Pan MacMillan | isbn = 978-0-330-44237-4}}</ref> is placed in the genus ''[[Russula]]'', the members of which are mostly known as '''brittlegills'''.  It is a variably colored mushroom, found in [[deciduous]] forests, and woods in [[Great Britain|Britain]], [[Europe]], and [[Scandinavia]].<ref name=C&D1995>{{cite book | author = Regis Courtecuisse and Bernard Duhem  | year = 1995 | title = Mushrooms and Toadstools of Britain and Europe | publisher = Harper Collins | isbn = 978-0-00-220025-7}}</ref> Appearing with broad-leaved trees in summer to early autumn, it usually has a greenish coloration.\n\n==Taxonomy==\nNoted and described by the [[South Africa]]n born [[mycologist]] [[Christian Hendrik Persoon]] as ''Agaricus lividus'' in 1801. It was placed in the ''[[Russula]]'' [[Genus]] by the Swedish mycologist, and botanist [[Elias Magnus Fries]] in 1838, with the epithet ''heterophylla''. Despite many changes, by several mycologists over the years since then, it is this binomial that is currently recognised,<ref>http://www.indexfungorum.org/Names/SynSpecies.asp?RecordID=193557</ref> and is in use at present.\n\nThe variants ''Russula heterophylla'' var. ''chlora'' Gillet 1876, and ''Russula heterophylla'' var. ''virginea'' (Cooke and Massee) A.Pearson & Dennis, have been given species status as ''[[Russula violeipes]]'', and ''[[Russula virginea]]'' respectively.\n\n==Description==\nThe [[pileus (mycology)|cap]] is {{convert|5|to|10|cm|in}} in diameter. It is known to vary in colour, and can be various shades of green, brown, or ochre. It is initially round, flattening with age, and laters develops a depression. The white [[stipe (mycology)|stem]] is firm, browning, and gives a salmon reaction when rubbed with [[ferrous sulphate]]. The [[Lamella (mycology)|gills]] are adnexed, and white giving a [[spore print]] of the same colour.<ref name=Phillips06/>\n\n===Microscopic characteristics===\nThe [[basidiospore|spores]] are the smallest in the genus, and are 5\u20137 by 4\u20136&nbsp;[[micrometre|\u00b5m]],  spherical to elliptical, or pear shaped; warts 0.2\u20130.6&nbsp;\u00b5m high, mostly isolated, but occasionally two or three joined together, or connected by a line.<ref name=Phillips06/>\n\n===Similar species===\nGreen forms of ''Russula cyanoxantha'' can be distinguished, because they give a greenish reaction, or no reaction when rubbed with [[ferrous sulphate]] (iron salts), and have the flexible, 'greasy' feeling gills characteristic of that species.\n\n''[[Russula virescens]]'' (Schaeff.) Fr.,  has a cracked or fragmented cap surface.\n\n''[[Russula aeruginea]]'' Fr.,  grows with [[Birch]].\n\n''[[Russula langei]]'' Bon, also has a green reaction to ferrous sulphate, and smells like shellfish, with flesh that stains orange-brown.\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\n''Russula heterophylla'' appears in summer to early autumn, usually growing in small groups. It is occasional in [[Great Britain|Britain]], [[Europe]], and [[Scandinavia]].<ref name=C&D1995/> It grows with several species of [[deciduous|broad-leaved]] trees, on the roots of which it is [[ectomycorrhizal]].\n\n==Edibility==\nThis mushroom is [[edible mushroom|edible]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Phillips |first=Roger |title=Mushrooms and Other Fungi of North America |year=2010 |origyear=2005 |publisher=Firefly Books |location=Buffalo, NY |isbn=978-1-55407-651-2 |p=141}}</ref> and good, although care must be taken as it is very like the deadly ''[[Amanita phalloides]]'' (death cap) when young. It is also prone to slug attacks.\n\n==See also==\n[[List of Russula species|List of ''Russula'' species]]\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.pbase.com/tmurray74/image/31682622 ''Russula heterophylla'']\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1415480}}\n\n[[Category:Fungi of Europe]]\n[[Category:Edible fungi]]\n[[Category:Russula|heterophylla]]\n\n\n{{Russulales-stub}}\n", "name_user": "UpdateNerd", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTaxonomy:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russula_heterophylla"}
